nks==\n* {{IMDb title|1483820}}\n{{K. S. Ravikumar}}\n\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Films directed by K. S. Ravikumar]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil film scores by Harris Jayaraj]]\n[[Category:Tamil films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Films about contract killing in India]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Typo fixing, replaced: stoped \u2192 stopped", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aadhavan"}
{"title_page": "Doug Bowden (rowing)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian rowing coxswain}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Douglas Bowden\n| headercolor = skyblue\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 24 Nov 1906\n| birth_place      = Glebe, Sydney\n| death_date       = 20 April 1996\n| death_place      = Lindfield, Sydney\n| residence        = \n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Hotel Management\n| years_active     = \n| spouse           = \n| height           = \n| nationals =\n| weight           = \n| sport            = Rowing\n| club = [[Glebe Rowing Club]] <br> [[North Shore Rowing Club]]\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[British Empire Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1938 British Empire Games|1938 Sydney]]|M8+}}\n}}\n'''Douglas William Bowden''' (24 Nov 1906 \u2013 20 April 1996) was an Australian rowing coxswain. He was twice a national champion and an Australian representative who won a silver medal at the [[1938 Commonwealth Games]].\n\n==Early life and rowing career==\nBorn in Glebe in Sydney, Bowden's father died when he was seven and he left school aged 14 to take employment with the brewery [[Tooth and Co.]] <ref name=\"C&B\" /> His early club coxing was from the [[Glebe Rowing Club]] where he was later in life honoured with a life membership.<ref name=\"C&B\" /> He next joined the [[North Shore Rowing Club]] in Sydney where he was both a coxswain and coach and had competitive and representative success. He coached the club's eight to victory in the 1937 Henley-on-Yarra in Melbourne.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/08-3.php|title=Sydney Rowing Club - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041102/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/08-3.php|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBowden first made state selection in the 1935 New South Wales men's eight which contested and won the [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] at the 1935 Interstate Regatta. He was the manager and the coxswain of that crew.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1935.php#M8|title=1935 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041115/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1935.php#M8|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1936 he again steered the New South Wales eight to another King's Cup victory.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1936.php#M8|title=1936 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214516/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1936.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was in the stern of the 1937 New South Wales eight which placed second at Murray Bridge in South Australia to the South Australian eight in that year's King's Cup.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1937.php#M8|title=1937 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214530/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1937.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1938 he was the coach of the New South Wales eight when they placed second to West Australia in the King's Cup. Then along with four of that crew he was selected in the Australian men's eight for the [[1938 Empire Games|1938 Commonwealth Games]]. That eight with Bowden as coxswain took the silver medal behind the British crew.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/commonwealth-games/1938-Sydney.html|title=1938 Sydney Empire Games - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228062611/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/commonwealth-games/1938-Sydney.html|archive-date=28 February 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter a some years' absence from competition due to [[WWII]], Bowden contested the New South Wales 1947 state title for eights in a [[North Shore Rowing Club]] crew of which he was cox and coach.<ref name=\"nla\">{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18018339?|title=24 Jan 1947 - PEARCE TO ROW IN EIGHTS|website=Trove|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing administrator and coach==\nIn 1939 Bowden was the manager of the New South Wales men's eight for the Interstate Regatta.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1939.php#M8|title=1939 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214511/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1939.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> After the war he was again the manager of the New South Wales men's eight for the Interstate Regatta in 1950.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1950.php#M8|title=1950 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> He was on the Regatta Committee for the 1952 Interstate Regatta held on the [[Nepean River]].<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1952.php|title=1952 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021111731/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1952.php|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 till 1977 Bowden was a rowing coach of the senior crews at [[St Joseph's College, Hunters Hill]]'s boatshed where his son had been educated in the 1950s. Doug Bowden was a co-coach of the school's first and second VIIIs and established an impressive record. At the [[AAGPS]] [[Head of the River (New South Wales)|Head of the River]] the school's first VIII placed second in 1970 and 1972 and won in 1971 and 1973. In 1973 the school's 2nd VIII was also victorious.<ref>St Joseph's College Magazine 1973.</ref> He was esteemed as an honorary Old Boy of the College.<ref name=\"C&B\" />\n\n==War service, professional and personal life==\nBowden enlisted in the [[2nd AIF]] in April 1942. He saw action in the Papua New Guinea on the [[Kokoda Trail]].<ref name=\"C&B\" /> On his discharge at war's end in September 1945 he was a private posted to the Queensland Line of Communication Area.<ref name=\"ww2roll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ww2roll.gov.au/Veteran.aspx?serviceId=A&veteranId=203425|website=ww2roll.gov.au|title=Bowden at World War Two Nominal Roll |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nPre and post [[WWII]] Bowden had a 50 year career with [[Tooth and Co.]] By the 1950s his role was as a management supervisor of the many hotels owned by the brewery throughout NSW and the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]].<ref name=\"C&B\" />\n\nBowden's longstanding marriage was to Isabel who pre-deceased him. They had two children, Lois and Peter and lived in Pymble, Sydney. Doug Bowden died aged 90 in 1996 following a series of strokes.<ref name= \"C&B\">Cerise & Blue (SJC OBU Magazine) May 1996 vol 38 #2</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowden, Douglas}}\n[[Category:Australian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Coxswains (rowing)]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Rowers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in rowing]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1938 British Empire Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian rowing coxswain}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name             = Douglas Bowden\n| headercolor = skyblue\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 24 Nov 1906\n| birth_place      = Glebe, Sydney\n| death_date       = 20 April 1996\n| death_place      = Lindfield, Sydney\n| residence        = \n| education        =\n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = Hotel Management\n| years_active     = \n| spouse           = \n| height           = \n| nationals =\n| weight           = \n| sport            = Rowing\n| club = [[Glebe Rowing Club]] <br> [[North Shore Rowing Club]]\n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{AUS}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[British Empire Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1938 British Empire Games|1938 Sydney]]|M8+}}\n}}\n'''Douglas William Bowden''' (24 Nov 1906 - 20 April 1996) was an Australian rowing coxswain. He was twice a national champion and an Australian representative who won a silver medal at the [[1938 Commonwealth Games]].\n\n==Early life and rowing career==\nBorn in Glebe in Sydney, Bowden's father died when he was seven and he left school aged 14 to take employment with the brewery [[Tooth and Co.]] <ref name=\"C&B\" /> His early club coxing was from the [[Glebe Rowing Club]] where he was later in life honoured with a life membership.<ref name=\"C&B\" /> He next joined the [[North Shore Rowing Club]] in Sydney where he was both a coxswain and coach and had competitive and representative success. He coached the club's eight to victory in the 1937 Henley-on-Yarra in Melbourne.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/08-3.php|title=Sydney Rowing Club - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041102/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/club-histories/sydney/08-3.php|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBowden first made state selection in the 1935 New South Wales men's eight which contested and won the [[King's Cup (rowing)|King's Cup]] at the 1935 Interstate Regatta. He was the manager and the coxswain of that crew.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1935.php#M8|title=1935 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929041115/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1935.php#M8|archive-date=29 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1936 he again steered the New South Wales eight to another King's Cup victory.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1936.php#M8|title=1936 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214516/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1936.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was in the stern of the 1937 New South Wales eight which placed second at Murray Bridge in South Australia to the South Australian eight in that year's King's Cup.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1937.php#M8|title=1937 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214530/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1937.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1938 he was the coach of the New South Wales eight when they placed second to West Australia in the King's Cup. Then along with four of that crew he was selected in the Australian men's eight for the [[1938 Empire Games|1938 Commonwealth Games]]. That eight with Bowden as coxswain took the silver medal behind the British crew.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/commonwealth-games/1938-Sydney.html|title=1938 Sydney Empire Games - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228062611/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/commonwealth-games/1938-Sydney.html|archive-date=28 February 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter a some years' absence from competition due to [[WWII]], Bowden contested the New South Wales 1947 state title for eights in a [[North Shore Rowing Club]] crew of which he was cox and coach.<ref name=\"nla\">{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18018339?|title=24 Jan 1947 - PEARCE TO ROW IN EIGHTS|website=Trove|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing administrator and coach==\nIn 1939 Bowden was the manager of the New South Wales men's eight for the Interstate Regatta.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1939.php#M8|title=1939 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012214511/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1939.php#M8|archive-date=12 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> After the war he was again the manager of the New South Wales men's eight for the Interstate Regatta in 1950.<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1950.php#M8|title=1950 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> He was on the Regatta Committee for the 1952 Interstate Regatta held on the [[Nepean River]].<ref name=\"rowinghistory-aus8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1952.php|title=1952 Interstate Championships - Australian Rowing History|website=rowinghistory-aus.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021111731/http://www.rowinghistory-aus.info/interstate-championships/1952.php|archive-date=21 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 till 1977 Bowden was a rowing coach of the senior crews at [[St Joseph's College, Hunters Hill]]'s boatshed where his son had been educated in the 1950s. Doug Bowden was a co-coach of the school's first and second VIIIs and established an impressive record. At the [[AAGPS]] [[Head of the River (New South Wales)|Head of the River]] the school's first VIII placed second in 1970 and 1972 and won in 1971 and 1973. In 1973 the school's 2nd VIII was also victorious.<ref>St Joseph's College Magazine 1973.</ref> He was esteemed as an honorary Old Boy of the College.<ref name=\"C&B\" />\n\n==War service, professional and personal life==\nBowden enlisted in the [[2nd AIF]] in April 1942. He saw action in the Papua New Guinea on the [[Kokoda Trail]].<ref name=\"C&B\" /> On his discharge at war's end in September 1945 he was a private posted to the Queensland Line of Communication Area.<ref name=\"ww2roll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ww2roll.gov.au/Veteran.aspx?serviceId=A&veteranId=203425|website=ww2roll.gov.au|title=Bowden at World War Two Nominal Roll |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nPre and post [[WWII]] Bowden had a 50 year career with [[Tooth and Co.]] By the 1950s his role was as a management supervisor of the many hotels owned by the brewery throughout NSW and the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]].<ref name=\"C&B\" />\n\nBowden's longstanding marriage was to Isabel who pre-deceased him. They had two children, Lois and Peter and lived in Pymble, Sydney. Doug Bowden died aged 90 in 1996 following a series of strokes.<ref name= \"C&B\">Cerise & Blue (SJC OBU Magazine) May 1996 vol 38 #2</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowden, Douglas}}\n[[Category:Australian male rowers]]\n[[Category:Coxswains (rowing)]]\n[[Category:Sportsmen from New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Rowers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in rowing]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1938 British Empire Games]]\n", "name_user": "Bkell", "label": "safe", "comment": "en dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doug_Bowden_(rowing)"}
{"title_page": "Shaheen Bagh protests", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{short description|2019\u201320 protests in India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Main|Citizenship Amendment Act protests}}\n\n{{Infobox protest\n|place=[[Shaheen Bagh]], Delhi, India\n| coordinates   = {{coord|28.5513|N|77.2970|E|region:IN_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|partof=[[Citizenship Amendment Act protests]]\n|image=Shaheen Bagh women protesters 15 Jan 2020.jpg\n|caption=Shaheen Bagh women protesters blocking a major road (Road 13A GD Birla Marg, Shaheen Bagh - Kalindi Kunj area) in New Delhi\n|date={{Unbulleted list||14 December 2019 \u2013 24 March 2020<ref name=\"100days\">{{cite news |last1=Bhasin |first1=Swati |title=Shaheen Bagh Anti-CAA Protesters Removed Amid Delhi Lockdown |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/delhis-shaheen-bagh-heart-of-anti-caa-protests-cleared-after-101-days-amid-lockdown-over-coronavirus-2199558 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The NDTV |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>|({{Age in years and days|month1=12|day1=14|year1=2019|month2=3|day2=24|year2=2020}})}}\n|causes=Passage of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] and the following [[2019 Jamia Milia Islamia attack|police intervention at Jamia Milia Islamia]]\n|status= Halted for [[lockdown]] imposed for curbing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n|goals= Pressurize Government to roll back CAA and not to implement NRC-NPR in the country, to revive economy and to take steps on unemployment and women safety\n|leadfigures1=''Non-centralized leadership''<br/>{{Efn|Media coordinator of Shaheen Bagh Protest: Qazi Emad<ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh protesters will have to follow ban on gathering over coronavirus: Kejriwal |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/shaheen-bagh-protesters-will-have-to-follow-ban-on-gathering-over-coronavirus-kejriwal/story-CYhB1EkHCAknZI7Wddg8VP.html |accessdate=19 March 2020 |agency=Hindustan Times |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>}}\n|methods=[[Protest]], [[Sit-in]], [[Demonstration (political)|Demonstrations]], [[Civil disobedience]], [[Hunger strike]], [[Slogan]], [[Public lecture]], [[Public debate]], Art ([[Graffiti]], [[Poster]], [[Scale model]], [[Political Poetry|Poetry]], [[Storytelling]], [[Street performance]], [[puppetry]])\n|fined=\n|arrests= 0 {{Efn|As a precautionary measure for the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|Coronavirus pandemic]], the protesters reduced the number of protesters at the site to just 5 individuals.<ref name=\"SB corona outbreak\"/> As complete [[Lockdown#Emergency lockdown|lockdown]] was imposed in Delhi from 23 to 31 March 2020,<ref name=\"lockdown Delhi\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Fallout: Delhi CM Arvind Kejriwal announces lockdown until March 31 |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-fallout-delhi-cm-arvind-kejriwal-announces-lockdown-until-march-31/articleshow/74761137.cms |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> the Delhi Police tried to remove the protesters from the site and on refusal by the police, the protesters who were present (assumed to be 5) were arrested on 24 March 2020.<ref name=\"100days\"/>}}\n|injuries= 1\n|detentions= 0 \n|fatalities= 0 {{Efn|A four month old child's parents told media that their child died in sleep in their tiny plastic shanty. It was reported that the child caught cold and congestion after got exposed during the winter chill as the mother was attending the outdoor protest.<ref>{{cite news |title=Infant dies after catching cold at Shaheen Bagh, mother to return for anti-CAA protest |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/infant-dies-after-catching-cold-at-shaheen-bagh-mother-to-return-for-anti-caa-protest-1642975-2020-02-03 |accessdate=16 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=3 February 2020}}</ref>}}\n|subtitle=Shaheen Bagh anti-CAA protests}}\n<mapframe latitude=\"28.543108\" longitude=\"77.303307\" zoom=\"13\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" align=\"right\">\n{\n\"type\": \"FeatureCollection\",\n\"features\": [\n{\n\"type\": \"Feature\",\n\"properties\": {},\n\"geometry\": {\n\"type\": \"Point\",\n\"coordinates\": [77.303307,28.543108]\n}}\n]\n}\n</mapframe>\n\nThe '''Shaheen Bagh protest''' was a [[sit-in]] [[Nonviolent resistance|peaceful]] [[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|protest]], led by women, that began in response to the passage of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|Citizenship (Amendment) Act]] (CAA) in both houses of [[Parliament of India|Parliament]] on 11 December 2019 and the ensuing police intervention against students at [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] who were opposing the Amendment.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-50902909|title=Shaheen Bagh: The women occupying Delhi street against citizenship law - 'I don't want to die proving I am Indian'|last=|first=|date=4 January 2020|work=BBC|access-date=2020-01-13|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108140153/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-50902909|archive-date=8 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/portraits-of-resilience-the-new-year-in-shaheen-bagh-11577952208794.html|title=Portraits of resilience: the new year in Shaheen Bagh|last=Bakshi|first=Asmita|date=2020-01-02|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064807/https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/portraits-of-resilience-the-new-year-in-shaheen-bagh-11577952208794.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/shaheen-bagh-residents-brave-the-cold-as-anti-caa-stir-enters-day-15/article30422794.ece|title=Shaheen Bagh residents brave the cold as anti-CAA stir enters Day 15|last=Reporter|first=Staff|date=2019-12-29|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064806/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/shaheen-bagh-residents-brave-the-cold-as-anti-caa-stir-enters-day-15/article30422794.ece|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Protesters have agitated not only against the citizenship issues of the CAA, [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC) and [[National Population Register]] (NPR), but also against police brutality, unemployment, poverty and for women's safety.<ref name=\"Shaheenbagheconomy1\"/> Mainly consisting of Muslim women, the protesters at [[Shaheen Bagh]], since 14 December 2019,<ref name=\":9\" /> have blocked a road{{Efn|Road No 13-A, Shaheen Bagh (GD Birla Marg) - Mathura Road - Kalindi Kunj - Shaheen Bagh stretch is a border point that connects New Delhi to Noida and Faridabad.|name=|group=}} in [[New Delhi]] using [[Nonviolent resistance|non-violent resistance]] for 101 days<!--DO NOT UPDATE THESE FIGURES WITHOUT AN UPDATED REFERENCE!--> as of 24 March 2020.<ref name=\"100days\"/><ref name=\":1\">References for validating duration of protest:\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest|title=Organiser 'Calls Off' Shaheen Bagh Anti-CAA Protest, Locals Continue Dharna|last=|first=|date=2 January 2020|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113061800/https://thewire.in/rights/shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13|url-status=live}}\n*{{Cite news|last=Arun|first=T. K.|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/view-lift-shaheen-bagh-now-carry-on-with-the-protest-in-other-forms/articleshow/74302377.cms|title=View: Lift Shaheen Bagh now, carry on with the protest in other forms|date=2020-02-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-02-25}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/anti-caa-protest-shaheen-bagh-hauz-rani|title=At Delhi's Anti-CAA Sit-In Protests, Women Continue Their Struggle|last=Nagpal|first=Muskan|date=4 March 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/international-women-s-day-spoilers-at-shaheen-bagh/cid/1752172|title=Spoilers on Women's Day at Shaheen Bagh|last=Vincent|first=Pheroze L.|date=9 March 2020|website=Telegraph India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-09}}\n*{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Shaheen Bagh protest to continue during Janata curfew |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/coronavirus-shaheen-bagh-protest-to-continue-during-janata-curfew/article31124975.ece |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |agency=PTI |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> It became the longest protest against CAA-NRC-NPR.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shaheen Bagh: Coronavirus clears long-running India citizenship protest |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52015464 |website=BBC |publisher=bbc.com |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> As a precautionary measure [[Delhi Police]] have barricaded the neighbouring major highways around the area. Following the [[North East Delhi riots]], police barricading and presence in the area increased with over ten companies, 1000 personnel, being assigned to Shaheen Bagh.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/heavy-security-section-144-in-delhi-s-shaheen-bagh-after-northeast-violence-11583061575169.html|title=Heavy security, Section 144 in Delhi's Shaheen Bagh after northeast violence|last=Das|first=Shaswati|date=2020-03-01|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The protests ended up on 24 March 2020 as Delhi Police vacated the site due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Delhi lockdown: Anti-CAA protesters removed from Shaheen Bagh, other places |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-lockdown-delhi-police-vacate-protesters-at-shaheen-bagh/articleshow/74785253.cms |website=ecomoictimes.com |publisher=India Times |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe leaderless protest has become politicized and is generally against the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) government.<ref name=\":1\" /> The protesters have also supported unions opposing the government's anti-labour policies and have protested against recent happenings such as the [[2020 JNU Attack]], and have shown solidarity with [[Kashmiri Pandit]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2020/jan/09/caa-protest-enters-27th-day-at-jamia-shaheen-bagh--2087091.html|title=CAA protest enters 27th day at Jamia, Shaheen Bagh|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113072601/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2020/jan/09/caa-protest-enters-27th-day-at-jamia-shaheen-bagh--2087091.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Support to Kashmiri Pandit\" /> The barricaded and tented venue has drawn large crowds; [[The Wire (India)|''The Wire'']] notes that tens of thousands of protesters have participated.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/watch-women-homemakers-lead-protests-against-caa-at-delhis-shaheen-bagh|title=Watch {{!}} Women, Homemakers Lead Protests Against CAA at Delhi's Shaheen Bagh|last=|first=|date=20 December 2019|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112102246/https://thewire.in/rights/watch-women-homemakers-lead-protests-against-caa-at-delhis-shaheen-bagh|archive-date=12 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref> The Shaheen Bagh protest has inspired similar ''Shaheen Bagh-style'' protests across the country, such as in Gaya, Kolkata, [[Prayagraj]], Mumbai and Bengaluru.\n\nThe blockade became a campaigning issue in the [[2020 Delhi Legislative Assembly election]]s. Some politicians promised to immediately remove the blockade after being voted into power, and were accused by their opponents of prolonging the demonstration to agitate voters. The blocked road affects more than 100,000 vehicles a day, adding hours to some journeys. As the area is also a border point into the capital, thousands of trucks are being diverted to other border points.\n\nFive petitions have been filed to stop the blockade. The [[Delhi High Court]] refused to hear the first two pleas and on 14 January 2020 declared the blockade to be a police matter. The [[Delhi Police]] have said that they will not use force to end the blockade. A third petition highlighted the difficulty faced by students with upcoming [[board examination]]s. The matter also reached the [[Supreme Court of India]] with two pleas being filed. Following the initial hearings, on 17 February the Supreme Court appointed three mediators to initiate conversations with the protesters regarding shifting to a location which doesn't block a public place. As of 5 March 2020 the second round of talks with the interlocutors is underway and the next hearing is on 23 March.\n\nEven after the spread of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus in India]], including additional restrictions enforced by the government under the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]], which includes a ban on gatherings of more than 50 people and the closure of schools, colleges, cinema halls and weekly markets among other things, the Shaheen Bagh protest still continued for several days. As a precautionary measure the protesters planned a more \"controlled gathering\" by reducing the number of protesters to just 5 individuals and symbolically placing cots and sandals by other protesters in solidarity.<ref name=\"HT SBagh 1\"/><ref name=\"SB corona outbreak\"/> However, following the complete [[Lockdown#Emergency lockdown|lockdown]] imposed in Delhi from 23 to 31 March 2020,<ref name=\"lockdown Delhi\"/> the protesters were arrested and forcefully removed from the site by the Delhi Police on 24 March 2020.<ref name=\"100days\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n=== Causes ===\n[[File:No NPR CAA NRC graffiti Shaheen Bagh protests New Delhi 8 Jan 2020.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Graffito of NPR-CAA-NRC in spray paint|No NPR CAA NRC graffiti at Shaheen Bagh]]\nOn 12 December 2019, the [[Parliament of India]] passed the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019]] (CAA), which amends the [[Indian nationality law|Citizenship Act of 1955]] to grant a swifter path to Indian citizenship under the assumption of [[religious persecution]] to any individual belonging to the specific religious minorities of [[Hindus]], [[Sikhs]], [[Buddhist]]s, [[Jain]]s, [[Parsis]] and [[Christians]] from [[Afghanistan]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[Pakistan]], for those who entered India on or before 31 December 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=195783|title=Parliament passes the Citizenship (Amendment) Bill 2019|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=21 December 2019}}</ref> However, the Act does not mention Muslims and does not offer eligibility benefits to Muslim immigrants or immigrants belonging to other religions or from other countries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/redefining-the-republic-citizenship-amendment-bill-6162526/|title=Citizenship law, proposed nation-wide NRC will revise conception of group rights in India|date=12 December 2019|website=The Indian Express|access-date=17 December 2019}}, Quote: \"Indeed, the CAB would only apply to undocumented Hindus, Sikhs, [...] would become \"refugees\" whereas Muslims [...] would remain illegal.\"</ref><ref name=\"MSNCAB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/newsindia/rajya-sabha-passes-citizenship-amendment-bill-what-is-a-hindu-and-why-are-myanmar-nepal-bhutan-sri-lanka-left-out-of-cab/ar-AAK0NL1|title=Rajya Sabha passes Citizenship Amendment Bill: What is a Hindu and why are Myanmar, Nepal, Bhutan, Sri Lanka left out of CAB? |website=MSN |access-date=16 December 2019}}</ref> such as [[Sri Lankan Tamils in India|Sri Lankan Tamil refugees]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shaji |first1=K.A |title=CAA: Sri Lankan Tamil Refugees Say The New Law Has Killed Their Hopes Of Citizenship |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/citizenship-amendment-act-sri-lankan-tamil-refugees_in_5dff246ce4b05b08bab6aff2 |accessdate=28 December 2019 |work=The Huffington Post |date=23 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Missing from India's citizenship law: 100,000 Sri Lankan refugees |url=https://www.malaymail.com/news/life/2019/12/28/missing-from-indias-citizenship-law-100000-sri-lankan-refugees/1822780 |accessdate=28 December 2019 |work=Malay Mail |date=28 December 2019}}</ref> [[Rohingya]] Muslim and Hindu refugees from [[Myanmar]], and [[Tibetan refugees in India|Buddhist refugees]] from Tibet.<ref name=\"WPCitizenship2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/12/13/indias-new-law-may-leave-millions-muslims-without-citizenship/|title=India's new law may leave millions of Muslims without citizenship|last=Chaudhry|first=Suparna|date=13 December 2019|website=Washington Post|access-date=18 December 2019}}</ref> It is also alleged that the [[National Register of Citizens]] (NRC), which the government plans to implement for the country in 2021, could be used to deprive Muslims of Indian citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/protests-continue-tamil-nadu-against-caa-nrc-1630224-2019-12-20|title=Protests continue in Tamil Nadu against CAA, NRC|first1=Akshaya|last1=Nath|date=December 20, 2019|website=India Today|access-date=22 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe CAA\u2013NRC issue also ignited protest of the economic crisis and economic disparities that the country is facing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/policy/all-modi-shah-are-doing-not-just-caa-and-nrc-is-to-polarise-on-communal-lines-yashwant-sinha|title=All Modi-Shah are doing, not just CAA and NRC, is to polarise on communal lines: Yashwant Sinha|last=Chandra|first=Abhimanyu|website=The Caravan|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref name=\"Shaheenbagheconomy1\"/> Women's safety, rising cost of commodities, increasing unemployment and poverty have acted as catalysts for the protest.<ref name=\"Shaheenbagheconomy1\">{{cite news |title=Not bothered who wins Delhi elections, say Shaheen Bagh protesters |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/elections/assembly-elections/delhi/not-bothered-by-delhi-results-say-shaheen-bagh-protesters/articleshow/73921690.cms?from=mdr |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pal |first1=Sumedha |title=Delhi Elections: At Shaheen Bagh, Youths Erect 'Unemployment Mirror of India' |url=https://www.newsclick.in/delhi-elections-shaheen-bagh-youths-erect-unemployment-mirror-india%E2%80%99 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Newsclick.in |date=4 February 2020}}</ref> The Indian economy has been witnessing a decreasing growth rate,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/underlying-causes-of-the-economic-slowdown/article30299555.ece|title=Underlying causes of the economic slowdown|last=Raghu|first=S. A.|website=@businessline|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> increasing household debt,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/borrow/indian-households-debt-doubles-in-fy17-18-what-are-we-borrowing-for-and-how-much/articleshow/67700374.cms|title=Indian households' debt doubles in FY17-18: What are we borrowing for and how much?|last=Bhardwaj|first=Sameer|date=2019-01-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> inflation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/inflation-shock-after-gdp-growth-slump-11578939727550.html|title=Inflation shock after GDP growth slump|last=Mishra|first=Asit Ranjan|date=2020-01-14|website=Livemint|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> unemployment<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/india-unemployment-rate-rises-to-3-year-high-of-85-in-october-cmie/story/387857.html|title=India's unemployment rate rises to 3-year high of 8.5% in October: CMIE|website=Business Today|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> and economic inequality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/indicators/why-india-needs-to-get-over-growth-numbers-and-look-beyond/articleshow/72944743.cms|title=Why India needs to get over growth numbers, and look beyond|date=2019-12-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> The [[State Bank of India]] estimated a growth rate of 4.6% for the [[Financial Year|financial year]] (FY) 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/state-bank-of-india-lowers-gdp-estimates-for-fy20-to-4-6-percent-from-5-percent/story/393413.html|title=SBI lowers GDP estimates for FY20 to 4.6% from 5%- Business News|website=Business Today|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> which would be the lowest since the [[2008 Global Recession]] where the growth rate had been 3.9%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2019/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=61&pr.y=6&sy=1980&ey=2024&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=534&s=NGDP_RPCH,PPPGDP,PPPPC,PPPSH,PCPIPCH,GGXWDG_NGDP&grp=0&a=|title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|website=IMF|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> The unemployment rate of India was reported to have reached a 45-year high of 6.1% in FY&nbsp;2017\u201318.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/unemployment-rate-at-five-decade-high-of-6-1-in-2017-18-nsso-survey-119013100053_1.html|title=Unemployment rate at four-decade high of 6.1% in 2017-18: NSSO survey|last=Jha|first=Somesh|date=2019-01-31|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> The Center for Monitoring Indian Economy stated the unemployment rate to be 8.45% with a rate of 37.48% for the 20\u201324 age group and 12.81% for the 25\u201329 age group in October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/opinion/others/easynomics-what-does-the-government-have-to-do-with-indias-unemployment-problem/articleshow/72133695.cms|title=Easynomics: What does the government have to do with India's unemployment problem?|date=Nov 20, 2019|website=Bangalore Mirror|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> According to the 2019 report of the [[Pew Research Center]], 393.7 million jobs are in a vulnerable state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/global/2019/03/25/a-sampling-of-public-opinion-in-india/|title=A Sampling of Public Opinion in India|last=Devlin|first=Kat|date=2019-03-25|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> [[Oxfam|Oxfam India]] data states that control of the country's wealth by the richest 1% of the population increased from 58% to 73% between 2018 and 2019, while the wealth of the poorest 50% increased by 1%. The WPS-index (Women, Peace and Security index) ranked India at 133 amongst 167 countries in 2019\u201320.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tracking sustainable peace through inclusion, justice, and security for women |url=https://giwps.georgetown.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/WPS-Index-2019-20-Report.pdf |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Georgetown Institute of Women, Peace and Security}}</ref>\n\n=== The protest ===\n[[File:Anti CAA NRC Shaheen Bagh New Delhi.jpg|thumb|220px|right|alt=Protesters in the freezing night of December|Protesters under a makeshift tent at the site during a night in December 2019.]]\nThe Shaheen Bagh protest was launched on the afternoon of 14 December 2019, when 10 to 15 local women began to blockade Kalindi Kunj Road (Road 13A<ref name=\"SarfarazVacate\" />), a six-lane highway bordering the Muslim-dominated neighbourhood of Shaheen Bagh in southeast Delhi. More locals joined and it became a continuous [[sit-in]] protest.<ref name=\":9\" /> Many of the women are [[hijab]]- and [[burqa]]-wearing Muslim homemakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/shaheen-bagh-protesters-vow-fight-seek-rollback-caa-law-200115032939000.html|title=Shaheen Bagh protesters pledge to fight, seek rollback of CAA law|last=Kuchay|first=Bilal|date=15 January 2020|website=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115085553/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/shaheen-bagh-protesters-vow-fight-seek-rollback-caa-law-200115032939000.html|archive-date=15 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> Elderly women have also joined the protest,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Badhwar |first1=Natasha |title=Speaking truth to power, in Shaheen Bagh and beyond |url=https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/speaking-truth-to-power-in-shaheen-bagh-and-beyond-11579260128955.html |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The Live Mint |date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petersen |first1=Hannah Ellis |last2=Azizur Rahman |first2=Shaikh |title='Modi is afraid': women take lead in India's citizenship protests |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/21/modi-is-afraid-women-take-lead-in-indias-citizenship-protests |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The Gaurdian |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> and children and newborn babies have been present with their parents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Salam |first1=Ziya Us |title=CAA protests: Making it count in Delhi |url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/the-nation/article30544019.ece |accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=The [[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] |publisher=The Hindu |date=31 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Muslim Women Occupy Streets in India Against Citizenship Law |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/01/24/world/asia/ap-as-india-womens-protest-photo-essay.html |accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=24 January 2020}}</ref> The protesters have been supported and coordinated by more than a hundred volunteers, including students and professionals from Delhi. These volunteers organized themselves around different tasks: setting up makeshift stages, shelters and bedding; providing food, water, medicine, and access to toilet facilities; installing CCTV cameras and bringing in outside speakers.<ref>{{cite news |title=The volunteers of Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/the-volunteers-of-shaheen-bagh/cid/1730063 |accessdate=8 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph (Calcutta) |date=25 December 2019}}</ref> Within 10 days, the peaceful protest had grown to cover nearly one kilometre (0.5&nbsp;mi) of the highway, supported by donations.<ref name=\"ReutersHow\">{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh sit-in: How Muslim women have taken the lead at Delhi CAA protest |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/biryani-bankers-and-burqas-inside-a-sit-in-protest-on-an-indian-highway-1631297-2019-12-25 |accessdate=8 February 2020 |agency=[[Reuters]] |work=[[India Today]]|publisher=[[Living Media|Living Media India]] |date=25 December 2019}}</ref> On 2 January 2020, some prominent volunteers withdrew and urged to stop the protest, fearing that its message could be hijacked by political parties with the approach of the [[2020 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi election]], which they felt could \"tarnish the image of the movement\" and raise the risk of violence.<ref name=\"SarfarazVacate\">{{cite news |last1=Sarfaraz |first1=Kainat |title=Shaheen Bagh protest organiser calls it off, can't get people to vacate |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/parties-hijacking-shaheen-bagh-protest-says-lead-organiser-calls-it-off/story-2IyPjvbChcMMaRyFdyv0tK.html |accessdate=8 February 2020 |work=The Hindustan Times |date=2 January 2020}}</ref> However, the women protesters immediately made it clear through social media that they would continue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Organiser 'Calls Off' Shaheen Bagh Anti-CAA Protest, Locals Continue Dharna |url=https://thewire.in/rights/shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest |accessdate=8 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ShaheenBaghProtest 26thJan2020 71stRepublicDay.jpeg|thumb|200px|left|alt=Huge crowd at Shaheen Bagh Protest|Shaheen Bagh Protest on 26&nbsp;January 2020, celebrating the 71st [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day of India]].]]\nWith crowds reaching as high as 100,000, the protest became one of the longest sit-in protests of this magnitude in modern India.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/unfazed-by-cold-200-women-stage-sit-in-at-shaheen-bagh-police-seek-to-end-protest-1631797-2019-12-26|title=Unfazed by cold, 200 women stage sit-in at Shaheen Bagh, police seek to end protest|last=PTI|date=26 December 2019|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226183717/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/unfazed-by-cold-200-women-stage-sit-in-at-shaheen-bagh-police-seek-to-end-protest-1631797-2019-12-26|archive-date=26 December 2019|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />  Its stages became a prominent platform to voice issues, and gained support from Punjab farmers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sikh Farmers from Punjab Join as Anti-CAA, NRC Stir at Shaheen Bagh Enters Second Month |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/sikh-farmers-from-punjab-join-as-anti-caa-nrc-stir-at-shaheen-bagh-enters-second-month-2459455.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The News18 |date=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mansa farmers join Shaheen Bagh stir |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/amritsar/mansa-farmers-join-shaheen-bagh-stir-more-from-sangrur-to-go-today/articleshow/73922471.cms |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=4 February 2020}}</ref> A number of protestors cited the [[2019 Jamia Milia Islamia attack]], in which about 200 student protestors were injured by Delhi police at the primarily Muslim JMI university.<ref name=\"SlaterErupt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/protests-erupt-across-india-against-new-citizenship-law-after-police-storm-university-campus/2019/12/16/9ebbeae6-1ff0-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html|title=Protests erupt across India against new citizenship law after police storm university campus|last1=Slater|first1=Joanna|work=Washington Post|accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref> [[CNN]] reported that a woman named Bahro Nisa quit her job to continue full-time protest, saying \"They tried to stifle the voices of our children [...] as mothers, we decided to stand up\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/14/asia/shaheen-bagh-muslim-intl-hnk/index.html|title=The women who have occupied a New Delhi street for a month|author1=Swati Gupta |author2=Manveena Suri |author3=Julia Hollingsworth|website=CNN|access-date=2020-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115095341/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/14/asia/shaheen-bagh-muslim-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> An article in ''[[Business Standard]]'' called the protest \"A new kind of ''[[satyagraha]]'' [English: civil protest]\", noting how a girl was allowed to express her doubts on stage by explaining her dilemma of supporting the CAA while understanding its dangers.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/shaheen-bagh-a-new-kind-of-satyagraha-with-a-fresh-grammar-of-protest-120011601102_1.html|title=Shaheen Bagh: A new kind of 'satyagraha' with a fresh grammar of protest|last=Datta|first=Pradip Kumar|date=2020-01-16|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 December 2019, thousands of camping protestors sang the [[Indian national anthem]] at midnight,<ref name=\"qz\">{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1778891/delhis-shaheen-bagh-women-keep-indias-caa-nrc-protest-alive/|title=At a women-led protest site in India, Muslims navigate identity, hope, and despair|last=Kapur|first=Manavi|date=3 January 2020|website=Quartz India|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113061756/https://qz.com/india/1778891/delhis-shaheen-bagh-women-keep-indias-caa-nrc-protest-alive/|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.millenniumpost.in/delhi/celebrities-activists-join-protesters-at-shaheen-bagh-to-celebrate-new-year-393726|title=Celebrities, activists join protesters at Shaheen Bagh to celebrate New Year|last=Abbas|first=Zafar|date=2019-12-31|website=www.millenniumpost.in|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113061800/http://www.millenniumpost.in/delhi/celebrities-activists-join-protesters-at-shaheen-bagh-to-celebrate-new-year-393726|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on what was reportedly Delhi's second-coldest night in the previous 100 years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/protesters-usher-in-new-year-2020-at-delhis-shaheen-bagh-with-national-anthem-2157039|title=Protesters Usher In New Year At Delhi's Shaheen Bagh With National Anthem|last=Dwivedi|first=Sukirti|date=1 January 2020|editor-last=Achom|editor-first=Debanish|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102195537/https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/protesters-usher-in-new-year-2020-at-delhis-shaheen-bagh-with-national-anthem-2157039|archive-date=2 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> The protest had one of its largest crowds on 12 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/biggest-crowd-at-shaheen-bagh-since-protest-began-4-weeks-ago/story-GamD6VlWuKa36kuxIWMLHI.html|title=Biggest crowd at Shaheen Bagh since protest began 4 weeks ago|last=Sarfaraz|first=Kainat|date=2020-01-13|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113084540/https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/biggest-crowd-at-shaheen-bagh-since-protest-began-4-weeks-ago/story-GamD6VlWuKa36kuxIWMLHI.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> On 26 January, the 71st [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day of India]], over 100,000 people assembled at the protest site.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amid Anti-CAA Protests, Thousands Join Flag Hoisting At Shaheen Bagh on Republic Day |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z1_kkY8P92s |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=The Quint |date=26 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Away from Rajpath, Shaheen Bagh 'celebrates the Republic' |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/away-from-rajpath-shaheen-bagh-celebrates-the-republic/articleshow/73647291.cms |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> The flag was hoisted by three local elderly women who became known as \"Shaheen Bagh ''dadis''\" (\"[[Grandparent|grandmother]]\" in Urdu) during the protest and by the mother of [[Suicide of Rohith Vemula|Rohith Vemula]].<ref>{{cite news |title=CAA protesters celebrate Republic Day all across India in their own unique way |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/caa-protests-republicday-india-shaheenbagh-kerala-1640391-2020-01-27 |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=27 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In Photos: Republic Day at Shaheen Bagh |url=https://thewire.in/rights/in-photos-republic-day-at-shaheen-bagh |accessdate=3 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> That day, [[Umar Khalid]] and [[Jignesh Mevani|Jigesh Mevani]] visited the area and delivered their respective speeches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/india-soul-protests-mark-republic-day-celebrations-200126140155387.html|title=India soul protests mark Republic day celebration, Shaheen Bagh|date=2020-01-26|website=AlJazeera|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nA health camp has also been set up beside the camped protesters. Doctors and nurses along with medical students from different medical institutes and hospitals voluntarily joined for the purpose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/at-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-stir-protesters-brave-biting-cold-24x7/story-gtSvJGXOycR6kq8tJ7kxwN.html|title=At Shaheen Bagh anti-CAA stir, protesters brave biting cold 24x7|date=2020-12-29|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113133807/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/at-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-stir-protesters-brave-biting-cold-24x7/story-gtSvJGXOycR6kq8tJ7kxwN.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"humansOfShaheenbagh\"/> Sikh farmers have also come and set up a ''langer'' (free community kitchen) in the area.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sikh-farmers-from-punjab-come-to-cheer-shaheen-bagh-women-cook-langar-2164508|title=Sikh Farmers From Punjab Come To Cheer Shaheen Bagh Women, Cook Langar|last=Rawat|first=Gargi|date=15 January 2020|editor-last=Sanyal|editor-first=Anindita|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115135957/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/sikh-farmers-from-punjab-come-to-cheer-shaheen-bagh-women-cook-langar-2164508|archive-date=15 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\nThe barricaded area has been visited by numerous politicians such as [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) leaders [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/mani-shankar-aiyar-addresses-protestors-at-shaheen-bagh-makes-contentious-remarks/articleshow/73262003.cms|title=Mani Shankar Aiyar addresses protestors at Shaheen Bagh, makes contentious remarks|last=|first=|date=15 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|agency=ANI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> and [[Shashi Tharoor]],<ref name=\":4\" /> social activist [[Chandrashekhar Azad Ravan|Chandrashekhar Azad]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shukla |first1=Saurabh |title=\"Women Fighting For India\": Chandrashekhar Azad's Message At Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/women-fighting-for-india-chandrashekhar-azads-message-at-shaheen-bagh-2168200 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The NDTV |date=23 January 2020}}</ref> and celebrities such as [[Mohammed Zeeshan Ayyub]].<ref name=\":2\" /> On 14 February 2020, filmmaker [[Anurag Kashyap]] visited Shaheen Bagh and delivered a speech.<ref name=\"kashyap\">{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh Protesters Pay Homage to Pulwama Martyrs, Anurag Kashyap Chips In |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/shaheen-bagh-protesters-pay-homage-to-pulwama-martyrs-anurag-kashyap-chips-in-2501579.html |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=The News18 |date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh too pays homage to the Pulwama martyrs |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u0u3ucNqJhk |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=The NDTV India |publisher=YouTube |date=14 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, the protestors also paid homage to the 40 martyred [[Central Reserve Police Force]] personnel in the [[2019 Pulwama attack]], a suicide bombing attack by terrorists.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh protestors pay tribute to Pulwama martyrs |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v6jgBRsGils |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=The Times Now |publisher=YouTube |date=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh protestors pay homage to Pulwama martyrs, Anurag Kashyap chips in |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/shaheen-bagh-protestors-pay-homage-to-pulwama-martyrs-anurag-kashyap-chips-in/1734737 |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=The Outlook |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n[[Protest art]] became the voice of resistance and dissent during the event,<ref name=\"Art of resistance\" /> and the area has been covered in murals, [[graffiti]], posters and banners.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Art of resistance\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/948440/the-art-of-resistance-ringing-in-the-new-year-with-anti-caa-protesters-at-shaheen-bagh|title=The Art of Resistance: Ringing in the new year with CAA protesters at Delhi's Shaheen Bagh|last=Venkataramakrishnan|first=Rohan|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106094833/https://scroll.in/article/948440/the-art-of-resistance-ringing-in-the-new-year-with-anti-caa-protesters-at-shaheen-bagh|archive-date=6 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/the-old-guard-meet-the-elderly-protesters-of-zakir-nagar-and-shaheen-bagh-11578659942897.html|title=The old guard: meet the elderly protesters of Zakir Nagar and Shaheen Bagh|last=Bakshi|first=Asmita|date=2020-01-10|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064808/https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/the-old-guard-meet-the-elderly-protesters-of-zakir-nagar-and-shaheen-bagh-11578659942897.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of [[scale model]]s were installed, including one of a [[Internment|detention camp]], depicting those used as a consequence of the [[National Register of Citizens for Assam|NRC in Assam]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mukhaerjee |first1=Paroma |title=Shaheen Bagh's revolution highway |url=https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/shaheen-bagh-s-revolution-highway-11580373131891.html |accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=The Live Mint |date=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=NRC and story of how Assam got detention centres for foreigners |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/nrc-story-how-assam-got-detention-centres-for-foreigners-1631835-2019-12-27 |accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=27 December 2019}}</ref> A miniature replica of [[India Gate]] bears the names of those killed during the anti-CAA protests across India. Protestors built and erected a {{convert|40|ft|m|0|order=flip|adj=mid|-high}} iron welded structure in the shape of India, painted with the message \"Hum Bharat ke log CAA-NPR-NRC nahi maante\" (English: We the people of India reject CAA-NPR-NRC).<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/the-colourful-dissent-when-shaheen-bagh-jamia-become-a-canvas-for-protest-6223028/|title=The colourful dissent: When Shaheen Bagh, Jamia become a canvas for protest|last=Beg|first=Sahil M|date=18 January 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> Hundreds of paper boats were arranged in the shape of a vast heart facing a small model battle tank; the boats were inscribed with the words of ''[[Hum Dekhenge]]'' (We will witness), a poem of resistance written by [[Faiz Ahmad Faiz]], with the many small and fragile boats dwarfing the tank which represented state oppression.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kataria |first1=Meenu |title=Different Faiths, One Voice: How Shaheen Bagh Protests Captured India's True Spirit Of 'Oneness' |url=https://www.scoopwhoop.com/news/shaheen-bagh-protests-captured-indias-true-spirit/ |accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=The Scoop Whoop |date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"humansOfShaheenbagh\"/> Posters proclaim that the protesters are \"a bouquet, not the [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus]]\" (the symbol of the ruling [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] [BJP]), giving the message of unity in diversity.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/950720/the-art-of-resistance-delhis-shaheen-bagh-has-turned-into-an-open-air-art-gallery|title=The Art of Resistance: Delhi's Shaheen Bagh has turned into an open air art gallery|last=Staff|first=Scroll|date=23 January 2020|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\nThe protest art has been [[Outsider art|made by anyone]], including students from Delhi University, JMI, Jadavpur University and Hyderabad Central University. A reading area called \"Read for Revolution\" had been set up with hundreds of crowd-sourced books as well as writing materials,<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/shaheen-bagh-juniors-draw-attention-to-caa/articleshow/73196513.cms|title=Delhi: Shaheen Bagh juniors draw attention to CAA {{!}} Delhi News - Times of India|last=Ajmal|first=Anam|date=11 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112211859/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/shaheen-bagh-juniors-draw-attention-to-caa/articleshow/73196513.cms|archive-date=12 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.in/index.php/en/NewsDetail/index/7/18148/Shaheen-Bagh-Kids-and-Jamia-Students-Make-Space-for-Art-Reading-and-Revolution|title=Shaheen Bagh Kids and Jamia Students Make Space for Art, Reading and Revolution|last=Thakur|first=Jyoti|date=11 January 2020|website=The Citizen|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064823/https://www.thecitizen.in//index.php/en/newsdetail/index/7/18148/shaheen-bagh-kids-and-jamia-students-make-space-for-art-reading-and-revolution|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> drawing allusions to the JMI attack in which police allegedly ransacked the university's library and assaulted those inside.<ref name=\":11\" /> On 17 January, a bus stop was converted into the [[Fatima Sheikh]]-[[Savitribai Phule]] library, which provided material on the country's constitution, revolution, racism, fascism, oppression and various social issues.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ameen |first1=Furquan |title=The Library at Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/delhi/the-fatima-sheikh-savitribai-phule-library-has-been-set-up-at-shaheen-bagh-on-17-january-2020-the-fourth-death-anniversary-of-rohith-vemula/cid/1737477 |accessdate=23 January 2020 |work=The Telegraph (Cacutta) |date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''<big>Image: Mural at Shaheen Bagh made during the protests</big>'''\n{{overlay\n|image=Cropped visual of wall art at Shaheen Bagh protests 7 Feb 2020.jpg\n|width=800\n|height=283\n|grid=no\n|overlay1=Words from the Preamble|overlay1left=340|overlay1top=50|overlay1tip=Lines from the Preamble|overlay1link=Preamble to the Constitution of India\n|overlay3=(transl.) Long live revolution for love|overlay3left=360|overlay3top=90|overlay3tip=Long live love|overlay3link=\n|overlay2=Cresent moon symbolism|overlay2left=260|overlay2top=84|overlay2tip=Cresent moon of Islam|overlay2link=Islamic calendar\n|overlay4=Constitution of India|overlay4left=250|overlay4top=180|overlay4tip=Constitution of India|overlay4link=Constitution of India\n|overlay5=Shaheen Bagh's ''dadis'' (grandmothers)|overlay5left=300|overlay5top=130|overlay5tip=ShaheenBagh's women|overlay5link=\n|overlay6=Shaheen falcon|overlay6left=350|overlay6top=140|overlay6tip=Shaheen falcon after which Shaheen Bagh is named|overlay6link=Shaheen falcon\n|overlay7=India's tricolours (saffron, white, green)|overlay7left=170|overlay7top=225|overlay7tip=Colours of the flag of India|overlay7link=Flag of India\n|overlay8=(transl.) Brave, Proud and Free woman|overlay8left=310|overlay8top=255|overlay8tip=The brave and proud woman of Shaheen Bagh|overlay8link=\n|overlay9=Peace and freedom sybolism|overlay9left=455|overlay9top=225|overlay9tip=Peace among communities and freedom of expression|overlay9link=Doves as symbols\n}}\nSpeeches, lectures and ''[[Urdu poetry|shayari]]'' poetry readings had been held every day (as of 31 December).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/delhi-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest|title=Shaheen Bagh Heralds a New Year With Songs of Azaadi|last=Chakrabarti|first=Samrat|date=31 December 2019|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101131334/https://thewire.in/rights/delhi-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest|archive-date=1 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> Lines of poetry and ''[[nazm]]'' of revolutionary poets such as [[Faiz Ahmad Faiz]], [[Pash]], [[Habib Jalib]], [[Muhammad Iqbal]] and [[Ramdhari Singh Dinkar]] were recited.<ref name=\":3\" /> Inter-faith prayers have been held.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2020/jan/13/anti-caa-stir-inter-faith-prayer-to-uphold-values-of-preamble-as-shaheen-bagh-protest-nears-month-2088707.html|title=Anti-CAA stir: Inter-faith prayer to uphold values of Preamble as Shaheen Bagh protest nears month|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064809/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/delhi/2020/jan/13/anti-caa-stir-inter-faith-prayer-to-uphold-values-of-preamble-as-shaheen-bagh-protest-nears-month-2088707.html|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/multi-faith-prayer-in-delhi-as-shaheen-baghs-caa-protest-nears-week-5-2162911|title=Massive Crowd, Multi-Faith Prayer At CAA Protest In Delhi's Shaheen Bagh|last=Roy|first=Divyanshu Dutta|date=13 January 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064809/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/multi-faith-prayer-in-delhi-as-shaheen-baghs-caa-protest-nears-week-5-2162911|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> Scriptures from the [[Bhagavad Gita|Geeta]], the [[Bible]], and the [[Quran]] have been read, and [[Gurbani]] was held.<ref name=\":4\" /> Many street pedlars have come to the site, including balloon vendors and ''chaatwallas'' (people cooking [[chaat]] from carts), giving the area a \"lightness of festivity\".<ref name=\":11\" />  Nearby eating establishments in Shaheen Bagh have seen an influx of people with an increase in political conversations, giving them a \"taste of revolution\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/mint-lounge/features/adda-and-lemon-tea-at-shaheen-bagh-11580364841235.html|title=Adda and lemon tea at Shaheen Bagh|last=Ramani|first=Priya|date=2020-01-30|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2 and 8 February 2020, a musical and cultural event called Artists Against Communalism was held in solidarity with anti-CAA protest. Performers included [[Hindustani classical music|Hindustani classical]] singer [[Shubha Mudgal]], [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] vocalist [[T.&nbsp;M. Krishna]], [[Sufism#Music|Sufi]] singer [[Madan Gopal Singh]], Ankur Tewari (music director of [[Gully Boy]]), singer [[Prateek Kuhad]], Kusha Kapila, and [[Anushka Manchanda]],<ref name=\"artists at Shaheenbagh\">{{cite news |last1=Das |first1=Aritry |title=Shubha Mudgal To Rapper Sumit Roy: When A Common Cause Makes Them Perform At Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-subha-mudgal-to-rapper-sumit-roy-when-a-common-cause-make-them-perform-at-shaheen-bagh/346916 |accessdate=9 February 2020 |work=The Outlook India |date=7 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Prateek Kuhad and many other artists perform in Shaheen Bagh in solidarity with anti-CAA protest |url=https://www.nationalheraldindia.com/india/prateek-kuhad-and-many-other-artists-perform-in-shaheen-bagh-in-solidarity-with-anti-caa-protest |accessdate=9 February 2020 |work=The National Herald (India) |date=6 February 2020}}</ref> and musical groups [[Advaita (band)|Advaita]], [[Peter Cat Recording Co.]], Moongphali and  [[Music of Rajasthan|Rajasthani folk]] troupe Kutle Khan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/stars-artists-caa-protest-shaheen-bagh-festival|title=Stars and Artists Line Up for Spontaneous Festival at Shaheen Bagh|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref name=\"PrateekKuhad\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/prateek-kuhad-singing-at-the-shaheen-bagh-protest-was-solidarity-not-a-free-concert-2489065.html|title=Prateek Kuhad Singing at the Shaheen Bagh Protest was Solidarity, Not a Free Concert|website=News18|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Mudgal performed the song \"''Hamari Khwaishon ka Naam Inquilab Hain''\" (English: My dream is my revolution) by poet Gorakh Pandey and \"''Main nahin janta, main nahin manta''\" (I refuse to acknowledge, I refuse to accept) by [[Habib Jalib]].<ref name=\"artists at Shaheenbagh\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Watch: Singer Shubha Mudgal joins CAA protest at Shaheen Bagh, sings Habib Jalib's 'Dastur' |url=https://scroll.in/video/952416/watch-singer-shubha-mudgal-joins-caa-protest-at-shaheen-bagh-sings-habib-jalibs-dastur |accessdate=9 February 2020 |work=The Scroll |date=7 February 2020}}</ref> Rapper Sumit Roy performed his viral rap music \"''Poorna Swaraj''\" (Complete freedom) and poet Amir Aziz recited \"''Main Inkaar Karta Hoon''\" (I refuse).<ref name=\"artists at Shaheenbagh\"/>\n{{quote box\n| width = 250px\n| bgcolor = #c6dbf7\n| align = right\n| quote = \"By insinuating that we don't know anything about CAA or NRC, Modi thinks he can diminish our protest. But we are aware, we have read the Act. We also know what the constitution says.\"\n| source = \u2014 Ghazala, 22, Shaheen Bagh protester<ref name=\"qz\"/>\n}}\n{{quote box\n| width = 250px\n| bgcolor = #c6dbf7\n| align = right\n| quote = \"We are Indians and we have all made this country what it is today. No one government should be able to tell us we are not Indians.\"\n| source = \u2014 Nahida Begum, 40, Shaheen Bagh protester<ref name=\"qz\"/>\n}}\n{{quote box\n| width = 250px\n| bgcolor = #c6dbf7\n| align = right\n| quote = \"I won't leave this country, and I don't want to die proving I am Indian. It's not just me, my ancestors, my children and grandchildren \u2013 we are all Indian. But we don't want to prove this to anyone.\"\n| source = \u2014 70-year-old protester Aasma Khatoon<ref name=\":0\"/>\n}}\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Art, graffiti and visuals from the protest site\">\nFile:Paper boats in the shape of a heart at Shaheen Bagh protests 15 Jan 2020.jpg|Paperboats artwork with ''[[Hum Dekhenge]]'' poem written on each\nFile:TankFacingBoatof HumDekhenge.jpeg|A miniature tank depicting state oppression resisted by a collection of paperboats arranged in heart shape\nFile:Hindu-Muslim-Sikh-Isai Graffiti.jpeg|Protesters reciting poetry around a [[Graffiti|graffito]] describing RSS trying to break the unity of Hindu-Muslim-Sikh-Isai.\nFile:Posters and artwork at shaheen bagh on closed storefront 7 jan 2020 new delhi.jpg|Posters and artwork on a closed storefront\nFile:35 feet high map of India made from 2.5 tons of iron by Pawan Shukla & Veer Chandra.jpg|A photo wall by JMI students; in background, a map of India inscribed with a rejection of CAA-NRC-NPR\nFile:State Oppression motive with CAA-NRC.jpeg|A graffito of popular rejection and resistance to societal oppression by the CAA-NRC\nFile:Posters at Shaheen Bagh 11 Jan 2020.jpg|A poster of Modi and [[Amit Shah]] as goons\nFile:Anti NRC CAA anti police shaheen bagh, new delhi poster 7 jan 2020.jpg|A poster mocking the [[Delhi Police]], connecting it with Hindu paramilitary group [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] (RSS).\nFile:Name of those killed in anti-caa protests on an India Gate artwork at Shaheen Bagh 11 Jan 2020.jpg|An [[India Gate]] mockup with names of those killed in anti-CAA protests\nFile:Ready for revolution poster shaheen bagh new delhi 2020.jpg|''Read for revolution'' and ''JNU is Bleeding'' poster following [[2020 JNU Attack]]{{Efn|The library and reading area is symbolic and a protest \"against the violent ransacking of the Jamia library and beating up of its readers by the Delhi Police.\"<ref name=\":11\" />|name=|group=}}  \n</gallery>\n\n== Hunger strike ==\nFew protesters were on hunger strike at the Shaheen Bagh. Zainul Abidin, a 29-year-old social activist and businessman from Jamia Nagar, had been on hunger strike since the protest started on 15 December 2019.<ref name=\"hunger strike\">{{cite news |last1=Kaur |first1=Pawanjyot |last2=Dhoundiyal |first2=Brijmohan |title=Meet the Anti-CAA Protesters On Hunger Strike at Shaheen Bagh |url=https://thewire.in/rights/watch-meet-the-anti-caa-protesters-on-hunger-strike-at-shaheen-bagh |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The WIre |date=15 January 2020}}</ref> 50-year-old social activist Mehroneesha began a hunger strike on 1 January 2020.<ref name=\"hunger strike\"/> Both stated that they were motivated by police brutality on the students of JMI along with perceived injustices of CAA-NRC.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet the Two Protestors on Hunger Strike Against CAA |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NEQIxzKSEgY |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Wire |publisher=YouTube |date=14 January 2020}}</ref> Abidin stated concern for his two sisters who were studying in Jamia, as police reportedly entered the toilets of the institute and beat the female students.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jamia ground report: Police entered mosque, beat up imam and me, claims former armyman |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/jamia-ground-report-police-entered-mosque-beat-up-imam-and-me-claims-former-armyman-1628843-2019-12-17 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=17 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Cops Entered Bathrooms, Libraries and Beat up Girls': Jamia Students Recount Sunday Night Horror |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/cops-entered-bathrooms-libraries-and-beat-up-girls-jamia-students-recount-sunday-night-horror-2425629.html |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The News18 |date=16 December 2019}}</ref> As of 10 February 2020, no government officials had visited the site or met with these hunger-striking protesters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vincent |first1=Pheroz |title=Shaheen soldiers on |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/shaheen-bagh-protest-soldiers-on/cid/1735318 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph (Calcutta) |date=13 January 2020}}</ref> Reportedly, Abidin was hospitalised and ended a 42-day hunger strike on 26 January 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi Congress President Subhash Chopra meets man on hunger strike at Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/delhi-congress-president-subhash-chopra-meets-man-on-hunger-strike-at-shaheen-bagh-120012600063_1.html |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Business Standard |date=26 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Children at the protest ==\n[[File:Children protesting with candle agaginst the CAA-NRC.jpeg|thumb|200px|left|alt=Children and Grafitti protest at Shaheen Bagh|Children sit-in protest around a graffito holding candles]]\nSince the first day, children have been present alongside parents who have participated in the protest.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tea, biryani, national anthem: How anti-CAA protesters in Shaheen Bagh welcomed 2020 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/delhi-news/shaheen-bagh-protesters-usher-in-new-year-with-national-anthem-bharat-mata-ki-jai/story-u1ZnXuMayQdulRgdbDX1mM.html |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=The Hindustan Times |date=1 January 2020}}</ref> Most of these children visit school in the morning before joining their parents at the protest site, which has become an art space for many children. They express their thoughts and join in the protest through [[storytelling]], poetry, [[puppetry]], singing and painting.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh protests in pictures: Graffiti, demonstrations on display against Citizenship Act, NRC |url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/news/india/shaheen-bagh-protests-pictures-citizenship-act-nrc-delhi-graffiti-demonstrations-578986 |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=The India TV |date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Purkait |first1=Aishik |title=In Shaheen Bagh, Children Paint Their Protest while Mothers Hold Dharna |url=https://in.makers.yahoo.com/shaheen-bagh-children-paint-protest-mothers-hold-sitdown-dharna-030626940.html |accessdate=22 January 2020 |work=Makers India |date=22 January 2020}}</ref> Student volunteers engaged the local children in reading, painting and singing, and held informal reading lessons.<ref name=\"humansOfShaheenbagh\">{{cite news |title=Human of Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ih_yQxpSIwA&t=315s |accessdate=14 February 2020 |work=The Quint |publisher=YouTube |date=14 January 2020}}</ref> \n[[File:Dressed up children at the Shaheen Bagh protests and a random person taking a selfie while others also take photographs.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Children at Shaheen Bagh protests|Children at the Shaheen Bagh protests dressed in tricolour]]\nChildren have drawn issues such as the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|Australian wildfires]] (with a child writing \"Shaheen Bagh prays for Australia\") and other things such as [[Deepika Padukone]], [[Spider-Man]] and [[Disney Princess]]es.<ref name=\":5\" /> Some of the children will go to the stage with slogans such as \"Hum kagaz nahin dikhayenge\" (we won't show our papers).<ref name=\":5\" /> One of the most common pictures drawn by the children is that of the [[national flag]].<ref name=\":5\" /> ''[[Scroll.in]]'' has called the area an \"open air art gallery\".<ref name=\":17\" /> Some children express themselves through sit-in protests holding candles.\n\nOn 21 January 2020, the [[National Commission for Protection of Child Rights]] (NCPCR), the top children's-rights body of India, asked authorities to provide counselling for children present at the protests.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/anil-baijal-delhi-lieutenant-governor-visits-shaheen-bagh-requests-end-to-protest-2167635|title=Delhi Lieutenant Governor Meets Shaheen Bagh Protesters, Calls For Peace|last=|first=|date=|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> A complaint was received claiming that the children had been misinformed by their parents about the CAA and [[National Register of Citizens#Detention Centres|detention centers]].<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/caa-protest-shaheen-bagh-ncpcr-flags-shaheen-bagh-protest-over-mental-trauma-to-children-2167855|title=Rights Body Flags Shaheen Bagh Protest Over \"Mental Trauma\" To Children|last=Roy|first=Divyanshu Dutta|date=22 January 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> Children at the site listen to speeches about issues \u2013 including CAA-NRC, the [[Ayodhya dispute]], and [[Triple talaq in India|triple ''talaq'']] ({{a.k.a.}} instant divorce) \u2013 which are claimed to have been discriminatory in nature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/on-eve-of-sc-hearing-shaheen-bagh-women-fast-write-postcards-to-cji/articleshow/73509525.cms|title=On eve of SC hearing, Shaheen Bagh women fast, write postcards to CJI|last=Venugopal|first=Vasudha|date=2020-01-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Some of these children have been seen in viral videos of the protests shouting slogans. [[NDTV]] reported that the District Magistrate of South East Delhi was informed of claims of \"mental trauma\" the children may have undergone due to this.<ref name=\":16\" /> After an infant died at the protests the Supreme Court questioned the Union and State governments as the why a four month year old child was at the protest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/supreme-court-must-stay-out-of-shaheen-bagh-it-cant-care-for-a-child-more-than-the-parents/362867/|title=Supreme Court can't care for Shaheen Bagh children more than the parents|last=Pai|first=Nitin|date=2020-02-11|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Efforts to remove blockade==\n<mapframe latitude=\"28.544531\" longitude=\"77.302766\" zoom=\"14\" width=\"240\" height=\"241\" align=\"right\">\n{\n\"type\": \"FeatureCollection\",\n\"features\": [\n{\n\"type\": \"Feature\",\n\"properties\": {},\n\"geometry\": {\n\"type\": \"Point\",\n\"coordinates\": [\n77.303307,\n28.543108\n]\n}\n},\n{\n\"type\": \"Feature\",\n\"properties\": {},\n\"geometry\": {\n\"type\": \"Polygon\",\n\"coordinates\": [[[77.29926824569704, 28.54185422673857,],\n[77.30289459228517, 28.54321140972318 ],\n[77.3041605949402,28.54388999465824],\n[77.30671405792238,28.546114214629867],\n[77.30735778808595,28.545793779055305],\n[77.31008291244508,28.54381459654799],\n[77.30988979339601,28.543531853153944],\n[77.30701446533205,28.545529890203095],\n[77.30428934097291,28.5434187555838],\n[77.30066299438478,28.541929626252006],\n[77.29950428009033,28.541458378407658],\n[77.29926824569704,28.54185422673857]]]\n}}\n]\n}\n</mapframe>\n[[Counter-protest]]s against the Shaheen Bagh blockade have been held with many locals wanting the roads to reopen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/protest-against-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protests-locals-want-stir-to-end-in-48-hrs-1636299-2020-01-13|title=Protest against Shaheen Bagh Anti CAA protests, locals want stir to end in 48 hrs|last=Yadav|first=Ankit|date=13 January 2020|website=India Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113064807/https://www.indiatoday.in/mail-today/story/protest-against-shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protests-locals-want-stir-to-end-in-48-hrs-1636299-2020-01-13|archive-date=13 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/anti-shaheen-bagh-protest|title=Protesters Chanting 'Jai Shri Ram' Stage Demonstration Near Shaheen Bagh|last=<!--no author listed-->|date=|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> The [[Delhi High Court]] refused a plea on shifting the protesters from Shaheen Bagh; the bench of the court was presided by the Chief Justice, [[Dhirubhai Naranbhai Patel|DN Patel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/hc-turns-down-plea-on-shifting-protesters-from-shaheen-bagh-1635649-2020-01-10|title=HC turns down plea on shifting protesters from Shaheen Bagh|last=|first=|date=10 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200111193957/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/hc-turns-down-plea-on-shifting-protesters-from-shaheen-bagh-1635649-2020-01-10|archive-date=11 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> Another petition has been filed by Advocate Amit Sahni \"seeking directions to withdraw the closure of Shaheen Bagh stretch\" and give Delhi Police the required assistance in addressing the issue.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livelaw.in/news-updates/shaheen-bagh-protests-plea-in-delhi-hc-seeks-reopening-of-stretch-closed-due-to-anti-caa-stir-151572|title=Shaheen Bagh Protests: Plea In Delhi HC Seeks Reopening Of Stretch Closed Due To Anti-CAA Stir|last=Tripathi|first=Karan|date=2020-01-13|website=www.livelaw.in|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113093729/https://www.livelaw.in/news-updates/shaheen-bagh-protests-plea-in-delhi-hc-seeks-reopening-of-stretch-closed-due-to-anti-caa-stir-151572|archive-date=13 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The blocked road affects more than 100,000 vehicles per day,<ref name=\":6\" /> including 1,800 trucks which are being diverted to other border points.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/shaheen-bagh-takes-toll-on-other-border-points/articleshow/73281531.cms|title=Delhi: Shaheen Bagh takes toll on other border points|last=Paras|first=Singh|date=16 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January 2020, the Delhi High Court stated that it was a traffic matter to be dealt with by the police according to the larger public interest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-high-court-kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-caa-protests-6215713/|title=Shaheen Bagh protest: HC asks Delhi Police to review traffic restrictions|last=|first=|date=14 January 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114102212/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/delhi/delhi-high-court-kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-caa-protests-6215713/|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-road-delhi-hc-disposes-of-plea-directs-police-to-manage-traffic-1636666-2020-01-14|title=Delhi HC directs police to look into restrictions on Kalindi Kunj-Shaheen Bagh stretch|last=|first=|date=14 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114100414/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-road-delhi-hc-disposes-of-plea-directs-police-to-manage-traffic-1636666-2020-01-14|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> The Delhi Police then stated that they would look into the restrictions caused by the protesters, which affect tens of thousands of commuters daily, including senior citizens, school children and office workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/delhi-hc-directs-police-to-look-into-restrictions-on-shaheen-bagh-stretch/story-CGL1CHksxWgPrrA5rZVjcP.html|title=Delhi HC directs police to look into restrictions on Shaheen Bagh stretch|last=|first=|date=14 January 2014|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114094531/https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/delhi-hc-directs-police-to-look-into-restrictions-on-shaheen-bagh-stretch/story-CGL1CHksxWgPrrA5rZVjcP.html|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/delhi-high-court-dismisses-plea-seeking-to-open-kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-stretch-says-polices-responsibility-to-manage-traffic-7902431.html|title=Delhi High Court dismisses plea seeking to open Kalindi Kunj-Shaheen Bagh stretch, says police's responsibility to manage traffic|last=|first=|date=14 January 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114101021/https://www.firstpost.com/india/delhi-high-court-dismisses-plea-seeking-to-open-kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-stretch-says-polices-responsibility-to-manage-traffic-7902431.html|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> Delhi Police made a statement saying that, \"Won't use force to evict protesters from Shaheen Bagh\" and would use \"persuasion\". (Notably, police brutality is among the protesters' grievances.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/shaheen-bagh-protest-caa-delhi-cops-told-to-use-persuasion-to-end-shaheen-bagh-blockade-sources-2163970|title=Delhi Cops Told To Use \"Persuasion\" To End Shaheen Bagh Blockade: Sources|last=Sharma|first=Neeta|date=14 January 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114153640/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/shaheen-bagh-protest-caa-delhi-cops-told-to-use-persuasion-to-end-shaheen-bagh-blockade-sources-2163970|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/won-t-use-force-to-evict-protestors-from-shaheen-bagh-delhi-police-after-court-order-1636836-2020-01-14|title=Won't use force to evict protestors from Shaheen Bagh: Delhi Police after court order|last=Pandey|first=Munish Chandra|date=14 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114153620/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/won-t-use-force-to-evict-protestors-from-shaheen-bagh-delhi-police-after-court-order-1636836-2020-01-14|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> Talks between the protesters and the police failed and the protesters refused to move.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/talks-between-delhi-police-and-anti-caa-protestors-at-shaheen-bagh-fail-women-refuse-to-move-1637540-2020-01-16|title=Talks between Delhi Police and anti-CAA protesters at Shaheen Bagh fail, women refuse to move|last=Sharma|first=Milan|date=16 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> The leaderless nature of the protests made it difficult to take any action.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThere have been various misleading claims by the media related to the incident. One of such claim was that the Delhi High Court ordered police to clear the protest site.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/949890/fact-check-delhi-high-court-did-not-order-police-to-clear-shaheen-bagh-protest|title=Fact Check: Delhi High Court did not order police to clear Shaheen Bagh protest|last=Daniyal|first=Shoaib|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114193826/https://scroll.in/article/949890/fact-check-delhi-high-court-did-not-order-police-to-clear-shaheen-bagh-protest|archive-date=14 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> ''[[The Times of India]]'' debunked a viral video which claimed there was a failed police crackdown at Shaheen Bagh; the video was from a CAA protest in East Delhi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/times-fact-check/news/fact-check-no-police-crackdown-at-shaheen-bagh-protest-site/articleshow/73321976.cms|title=FACT CHECK: No police 'crackdown' at Shaheen Bagh protest site|last=Times Fact Check|date=17 January 2020|website=The Times of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n[[File:A huge art installation at the site of the Shaheen Bagh protests made by protesters 17 Jan 2020.jpg|thumb|200px|left|alt=A huge art installation at the site of the Shaheen Bagh protests made by protesters 17 Jan 2020|The protest site on GD Birla Marg]]\nOn 17 January 2020, Delhi Lt. Governor [[Anil Baijal]] gave the Delhi Police authorization to detain anyone under the [[National Security Act (India)|National Security Act]], for three months beginning on 19 January.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/days-after-hc-order-on-shaheen-bagh-protests-lg-empowers-delhi-cp-to-detain-anyone-for-next-3-months/story/394070.html|title=Days after HC order on Shaheen Bagh protests, LG empowers Delhi CP to detain anyone for next 3 months|last=|first=|date=17 January 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> This was reportedly clarified by the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Home Ministry]] as a routine order.<ref name=\":12\" /> On 18 January, another petition was filed by Advocate Amresh Mathur on behalf of the [[Sarita Vihar]] [[resident welfare association]] (RWA) for opening the road, with concerns regarding the upcoming student [[board exams]] in February and March. The High Court accordingly directed the police to look into the reasons for the closure.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-hc-directs-police-to-look-into-kalindi-kunj-shaheen-bagh-blockage-causing-difficulty-for-students/articleshow/73352202.cms|title=Delhi HC directs police to look into Kalindi Kunj-Shaheen Bagh blockage causing difficulty for students|last=|first=|date=2020-01-18|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-01-19|url-status=live|agency=ANI}}</ref>\n\nDelhi BJP chief [[Manoj Tiwari]] made a video appeal to the protesters to end the demonstration, noting that the road closure resulted in tens of thousands \"completing a 25-minute journey in two-three hours\", while stating that the CAA was not against any religion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/citizenship-amendment-act-delhi-bjp-chief-manoj-tiwaris-video-appeal-to-caa-protesters-at-shaheen-ba-2164254|title=Delhi BJP's Manoj Tiwari's Video Appeal To CAA Protesters At Shaheen Bagh|last=|first=|date=15 January 2020|editor-last=Bhasin|editor-first=Swati|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115135626/https://www.ndtv.com/delhi-news/citizenship-amendment-act-delhi-bjp-chief-manoj-tiwaris-video-appeal-to-caa-protesters-at-shaheen-ba-2164254|archive-date=15 January 2020|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref> Protesters responded that they would not budge until CAA is scrapped, but that they will help ease traffic,<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/will-help-ease-traffic-but-wont-move-says-delhis-shaheen-bagh-after-hc-order-to-police/349525/|title=Will help ease traffic but won't move, say Delhi's Shaheen Bagh CAA protesters after HC order|last=Khan|first=Fatima|date=2020-01-14|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115051237/https://theprint.in/india/will-help-ease-traffic-but-wont-move-says-delhis-shaheen-bagh-after-hc-order-to-police/349525/|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and said that they have opened the blockade for ambulances and would do so for school buses.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOn 21 January, Baijal met a group of eight protesters who submitted a memorandum of demands.<ref name=\":14\" /> On 1 February, Union Minister [[Ravi Shankar Prasad]] said that the [[Narendra Modi Government|Narendra Modi government]] was ready to negotiate in a structured manner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/centre-ready-to-talk-to-shaheen-bagh-protesters-but-in-a-structured-form-ravi-shankar-prasad/articleshow/73833484.cms|title=Ravi Shankar Prasad: Centre ready to talk to Shaheen Bagh protesters but in a structured form|last=PTI|date=1 February 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/government/shaheen-bagh-ravi-shankar-prasad|title=Talks With Shaheen Bagh Protesters Must Be in Structured Form: Ravi Shankar Prasad|website=The Wire|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\nCommentators have noted that the Shaheen Bagh is allowed to continue as it benefits the regime. [[Pratap Bhanu Mehta]] noted that \"In Delhi, the protests were allowed to continue in Shaheen Bagh, not because the government was soft. It thought it could use the protest as pretext to consolidate majoritarian sentiment: Look at these minorities blocking roads and standing against Hindu rights, went the refrain.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/delhi-violence-riots-police-caa-npr-6288323/|title=The Delhi darkness: Our rulers want an India that thrives on cruelty, fear, division, violence|last=Mehta|first=Pratap Bhanu|date=2020-02-29|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Police blockades ===\n[[File:Graffiti on police barricades no nrc caa road blocked for protesters who have been sitting for over three weeks in background New Delhi 7 Jan 2020.jpg|thumb|220px|right|alt=No CAA-NRC painted on police barricades|Police barricades blocking the carraige ways of GD Birla Marg]]\n''[[Scroll.in]]'' reported that the effect on traffic congestion was not merely due to the closure of GD Birla Marg, but also because two alternative routes had been barricaded by Delhi and Uttar Pradesh (UP) police. ''[[The Quint]]'' reported that the protest occupied a small stretch of GD Birla Marg, one of the roads that connects Delhi to [[Noida]], whereas police blocked both the carriage way and the whole road.<ref>{{cite news |title=Traffic Inconvenience Vs Human Rights: Why Shaheen Bagh Must Stand |url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/hot-take/why-shaheen-bagh-protest-cant-stop-for-traffic-problems |accessdate=15 February 2020 |work=The Quint |date=17 January 2020}}</ref> The first set of barricades were placed ahead of the GD Birla Marg Bridge, but a second set of police barricades were placed {{convert|200|m}} to the west. This resulted the blockade of Jasola Vihar Main Road and Allama Shiibli Road which could connect Sarita Vihar to Jamia Nagar. ''Scroll.in'' could not determine why the police had closed this additional stretch.<ref name=\"Police blockade\">{{cite news |last1=Lalwani |first1=Vijayta |title=Why have Delhi and UP Police blocked alternative routes around Shaheen Bagh? |url=https://scroll.in/article/952617/why-have-delhi-and-up-police-blocked-alternative-routes-around-shaheen-bagh |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Scroll.in |date=10 February 2020}}</ref> Delhi Police called this \"a security measure\". UP Police, on the other hand, blamed the Delhi Police for erecting barricades blocking the entry of commuters from Noida into Delhi, citing the Kalindi Kunj\u2013Mithapur Road blockade. Since Delhi Police blocked the entry point near Kalindi Kunj metro station, UP Police had to block the road on the UP side at Kalindi Kunj Bridge.<ref name=\"Police blockade\"/> Delhi Police also blocked the entry of Khadar\u2013Kalindi Kunj Road which connects Jamia Nagar and Noida to Faridabad.<ref name=\"Police blockade\"/> Following the [[North East Delhi riots]], police barricading and presence in the area increased with over ten companies (1000 personnel) being deployed in the area.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n=== Petitions in Supreme Court ===\nA plea was filed in the [[Supreme Court of India]] requesting supervision of the matter so as to prevent any violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/plea-in-sc-over-traffic-blockade-in-delhi-s-shaheen-bagh/story-t4y0HTc0LVdfT9rdcqWxBJ.html|title=Plea in Supreme Court over traffic blockade in Delhi's Shaheen Bagh|date=2020-01-20|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|via=Press Trust of India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> The plea sought removal of the demonstration, citing that no one can be allowed to occupy a public road under the pretext of peaceful protest and for an indefinite period such that others face inconvenience.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rajagopal |first1=Krishnadas |title=SC to hear pleas against protest at Shaheen Bagh on February 10 |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/sc-to-hear-pleas-against-protest-at-shaheen-bagh-on-february-10/article30759512.ece |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=7 February 2020}}</ref> Another Supreme Court petition was filed later, on 4 February 2020, by BJP leader [[Nand Kishore Garg]] and sought an urgent hearing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/bjp-leader-seeks-urgent-sc-hearing-for-removal-of-shaheen-bagh-protesters/article30733062.ece|title=BJP leader seeks urgent SC hearing for removal of Shaheen Bagh protesters|last=PTI|date=|website=The Hindu BusinessLine|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> On 7 February, the Supreme Court postponed the hearing until after the Delhi elections (scheduled for 8 February), so as not to influence the outcome.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/petition-to-remove-shaheen-bagh-protesters-to-be-heard-on-monday-after-delhi-election-says-supreme-c-2176390|title='Cat Out Of Bag': Top Court To Hear Shaheen Bagh Case After Delhi Polls|last=Vaidyanathan|first=A|date=7 February 2020|editor-last=Srinivasan|editor-first=Chandrashekar|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> On 10 February, in its first hearing, the Court drew the attention of the protesters to the inconvenience caused over months of disruption. The court argued whether protests can be held in common areas indefinitely or if an area should be designated for protests, and considered the consequences of such protests held in public areas everywhere.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rajagopal |first1=Krishnadas |title=Shaheen Bagh closure: There cannot be indefinite protest in common area, says SC |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/shaheen-bagh-closure-there-cannot-be-indefinite-protest-in-common-area-says-sc/article30782154.ece?homepage=true |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=10 February 2010}}</ref> However, the Court issued notices to the Central Government, the Delhi Government and the Delhi Police, stating that people have the \"right to protest\" though this couldn't be for \"an indefinite period in a common area\". The Court did not give any interim order and wanted to hear from the protesters.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaidyanathan |first1=A |last2=Ghosh |first2=Deepshikha |title=Can't Block Public Road Indefinitely: Top Court On Shaheen Bagh Protest |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/shaheen-bagh-supreme-court-notice-to-centre-delhi-police-says-protests-cant-go-on-for-indefinite-per-2177755 |accessdate=10 February 2020 |work=The NDTV |date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February, the Supreme Court heard the plea, which framed the matter as an issue of protests on public roads. Two interlocutors have been chosen for engagement in dialogues with the protesters by the bench of justices [[Sanjay Kishan Kaul|S.K. Kaul]] and [[K. M. Joseph]] and the hearing was scheduled for 24 February 2020. The two interlocutors are senior advocates Sanjay Hegde and Sadhna Ramchandran.<ref name=\"India Today SC interlocutors\">{{cite news |last1=Pallwal |first1=Aishwarya |title=Shaheen Bagh kayam rahe, only here to talk about roads: Sadhana Ramachandran on Day 4 of mediation |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shaheen-bagh-supreme-court-appointed-interlocutors-day-4-mediation-talks-sadhana-ramachandran-1648957-2020-02-22 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=22 February 2020}}</ref> The Court also advised the interlocutors that they could seek assistance former [[Chief Information Commissioner of India]], [[Wajahat Habibullah]] who filed an affidavit in the Court on the blockade.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh mediator tells SC protest peaceful, police block roads |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shaheen-bagh-interlocutor-sc-protest-peaceful-police-block-roads-1649193-2020-02-23 |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The India Today |date=23 February 2020}}</ref> Habibullah in his affidavit stated the court that the precautionary blockade by police around the protest site is cause for the traffic inconveniences.<ref>{{cite news |title=Delhi Police, Not Protestors, to Blame for Traffic Around Shaheen Bagh: Ex CIC Tells SC |url=https://thewire.in/government/shaheen-bagh-traffic-delhi-police-wajahat-habibullah |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=23 February 2020}}</ref> Hegde and Ramachandran examined the area and had several talk sessions with the protesters. On 24 February 2020, the interlocutors submitted the [[Under seal|sealed cover]] report to the court as the report was only meant to be studied by court.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahajan |first1=Shruti |title=Shaheen Bagh Protests: Interlocutors hand over report to Supreme Court in sealed cover |url=https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/shaheen-bagh-protests-interlocutors-hand-over-report-to-supreme-court-in-sealed-cover |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Bar and Bench |date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Supreme Court: Interlocutors Submit 'Sealed Cover' Report on Shaheen Bagh Protest |url=https://thewire.in/law/supreme-court-interlocutors-submit-sealed-cover-report-on-shaheen-bagh-protest |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Wire |date=24 February 2020}}</ref> The bench received the report to examine the situation and scheduled the hearing for 26 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Interlocutors file sealed report in Supreme Court after talks with Shaheen Bagh protesters |url=https://theprint.in/india/interlocutors-file-sealed-report-in-supreme-court-after-talks-with-shaheen-bagh-protesters/370168/ |accessdate=25 February 2020 |work=The Print |date=24 February 2020}}</ref> However, the Court postponed the hearing for 23 March 2020, following the [[North East Delhi riots]] happened between 23 and 26 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=SC to hear Shaheen Bagh matter on March 23 |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/sc-to-hear-shaheen-bagh-matter-on-march-23-120022600406_1.html |accessdate=27 February 2020 |work=ANI |publisher=The Livemint |date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The second round of talks between the interlocutors and the protesters is underway as of 5 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/round-two-of-shaheen-bagh-talks-begin-interlocutors-play-holi-card-for-positive-solution/375192/|title=Round two of Shaheen Bagh talks begin, interlocutors play Holi card for 'positive solution'|last=Roy|first=Debayan|date=2020-03-04|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n== Defamation attempts ==\n=== Kashmiri Pandits' cause ===\n{{quote box |width=250px |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |quote=\"We feel the pain of Kashmiri Pandits who left everything back in Kashmir and ran. We the people of Shaheen Bagh stand in solidarity with them in their agony.\"|source=\u2014 A 40-year-old female protester at Shaheen Bagh.<ref name=\"kashmiri pandit shaheen bagh\">{{cite news |last1=Mir |first1=Shoaib |title=Kashmiri Pandits Join Resistance Celebrations at Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.thecitizen.in/index.php/en/NewsDetail/index/9/18193/-Kashmiri-Pandits-Join-Resistance-Celebrations-at-Shaheen-Bagh |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Citizen |date=20 January 2020}}</ref>}}\nOn 19 January 2020, the protesters at Shaheen Bagh called for a meeting in solidarity with the [[Kashmiri Pandit]]s, who were the victims of the [[Exodus of Kashmiri Hindus|exodus in Kashmir]].<ref name=\"kashmiri pandit shaheen bagh\"/> This was observed after a controversial [[Twitter#Tweets|tweet]] by filmmaker [[Vivek Agnihotri]] went viral, claiming that the protesters of Shaheen Bagh would organise an event to celebrate \"Kashmiri Hindu Genocide day\" on that day, which the official twitter handle of Shaheen Bagh debunked. A statement was released which clarified that \"malicious elements\" were circulating false information on social media, and that the event was not to commemorate the exodus.<ref>{{cite news |title=January 19 event has nothing to do with Kashmiri Pandit exodus: Shaheen Bagh protestors |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/january-19-event-has-nothing-to-do-with-kashmiri-pandit-exodus-shaheen-bagh-protestors-1638144-2020-01-18 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The India Today |date=18 January 2020}}</ref> The protesters also recognised the \"injustice done\" to the Kashmiri Pandits and invited them to the Shaheen Bagh protest site, where they observed a two-minute silence in solidarity. Two prominent Kashmiri Pandits, performance artist Inder Salim and theatre personality [[M.&nbsp;K. Raina]], delivered a speech at the gathering.<ref name=\"Support to Kashmiri Pandit\">{{cite news |last1=Ashraf |first1=Asad |title=Shaheen Bagh protesters express solidarity with Kashmiri Pandits on exodus day |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kashmiri-pandits-exodusday-migration-refugees-1638294-2020-01-19 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The India Today |date=19 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh Observes 2-minute Silence for Kashmiri Pandits in Solidarity Show |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/shaheen-bagh-observes-2-minute-silence-for-kashmiri-pandits-in-solidarity-show-2464813.html |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The News18 |date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Paid protest allegations ===\n[[File:Shaheen Bagh protests blocking a major road in New Delhi for 28 days Visual from 11 Jan 2020.jpg|thumb|180px|left|alt=A poster of Shaheenbagh protest describing not to give money to any protesters or volunteer to join the protest|A poster at the protest reads: No Cash, No Paytm, No Account (Don't give money to any volunteers)<br/><small>''Photographed'', 11 Jan 2020</small>]]\nAs the protest entered January, the BJP and its online supporters made claims that protesters were being paid. A doctored poster stating \"fix rate RS&nbsp;500\" went viral on social media platforms on 18&nbsp;January 2020. This claim was debunked when independent website ''The Logical Indian'' released a [[Fact checking|fact check]] article on the same posters. The article unearthed the veracity of the real poster which says, \"CAA wapas lo, NRC wapas lo\" (English: Roll back CAA and NRC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Fact Check: Poster From Shaheen Bagh Protest Wrongly Claims Protestors Paid Rs 500 Per Day|url=https://thelogicalindian.com/fact-check/shaheen-bagh-protest-anti-caa-nrc-muslim-women-poster-fake-news-19373 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Logical Indian |date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nPosters at the site asked participants to not accept any amount of money and to not bribe anyone to participate.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"No Cash, No Paytm\" Posters At Shaheen Bagh To Refute Claims Of Paid Protests |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/no-cash-no-paytm-posters-in-shaheen-bagh-to-refute-claims-of-paid-protests-2166212 |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The NDTV |date=19 January 2020}}</ref> On 15 January, Amit Malviya, BJP leader and head of IT cell, tweeted a video which claims that the women protesters had been paid {{INR|500 to 700|link=yes}} to sit-in.<ref>{{cite news|title=BJP IT cell chief claims Shaheen Bagh protesters paid Rs 500/day |url=https://www.siasat.com/bjp-it-cell-chief-claims-shaheen-bagh-protesters-paid-rs-500-day-1794465/ |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Siasat Daily |date=16 January 2020}}</ref> The protest's official Twitter account released a statement and denied the claim.<ref name=\":15\" />\n{{quote box |width=250px |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |quote=\"We are not here to take Rs 500 rather we are here to protect our 500 years which our ancestors have dedicated for India.\"|source=\u2014 Asharfi, a 63-year-old protester.<ref>{{cite news|title=Not for Rs 500, we are here to protect our 500 yrs: Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.siasat.com/caa-nrc-no-cash-no-paytm-posters-shaheen-bagh-1797445/ |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Siasat Daily |date=19 January 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nOn 4 February 2020, ''[[AltNews.in|AltNews]]'' and ''Newslaundry'' jointly released a [[Fact-checking#Detecting fake news|fact-check]]ing article in which the veracity of the video was debunked. It was discovered that the video was orchestrated by a shop owner in his shop in [[Tughlakabad (Delhi Assembly constituency)|Tughlakabad]] of South Delhi. This demonstrated how the mainstream media's lack of [[Journalism ethics and standards|ethical journalism]] helped to create a false narrative and a negative image of the protest.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Jignesh |last2=Tiwari |first2=Ayush |title=Truth about \"sting\" claiming Shaheen Bagh women were paid Rs 500: Alt News-Newslaundry joint investigation |url=https://www.altnews.in/truth-about-sting-claiming-shaheen-bagh-women-were-paid-rs-500-alt-news-newslaundry-joint-investigation/ |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=[[AltNews.in]] |date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Patel |first1=Jignesh |last2=Tiwari |first2=Ayush |title=The truth about Amit Malviya's Shaheen Bagh expos\u00e9: An Alt News and Newslaundry investigation |url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2020/02/04/the-truth-about-amit-malviyas-shaheen-bagh-expos-an-alt-news-and-newslaundry-investigation |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=The Newslaundry |date=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo female protesters named Nafisa Bano and Shahzad Fatma sent a [[Defamation#India|defamation notice]] to Malviya which demanded an apology and {{INR|1&nbsp;crore}} (10&nbsp;million rupees) in damages from the BJP leader.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh Women Send Defamation Notice to BJP IT Cell Chief |url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/shaheen-bagh-women-protesters-send-defamation-notice-to-bjp-it-cell-chief-amit-malviya-false-allegations-paid-to-sit |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Quint |date=21 January 2020}}</ref> The notice alleges that the addressees, \"have not only played a fraud on the general public but have also attempted to bring disrepute to the protesters\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shaheen-bagh-women-send-defamation-notice-to-bjp-it-cell-chief-amit-malviya-over-paid-protest-charge-1638598-2020-01-20|title=Shaheen Bagh women send defamation notice to BJP IT cell chief Amit Malviya over paid protest charge|last=|first=|date=20 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> ''[[The Quint]]'' reported that on 21 January notices had also been sent to ''[[Republic TV]]'', ''[[Zee News]]'', ''[[Times Now]]'', ''[[TV18]]'' and ''[[News Nation]]'' with the same allegations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/shaheen-bagh-women-protesters-send-defamation-notice-to-bjp-it-cell-chief-amit-malviya-false-allegations-paid-to-sit|title=Shaheen Bagh Women Send Notice to BJP IT Cell Chief, 5 TV Channels|date=2020-01-21|website=The Quint|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n== Inspiration for other similar protests ==\nThe Shaheen Bagh protest has inspired several other similar protests in big cities around India. On 7 January 2020, female residents of [[Park Circus]], Kolkata, gathered at Park Circus Maidan to voice their dissent against the CAA. It became one of the most organised protests against CAA-NRC.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Doulatramani |first1=Chandni |title=Shaheen Bagh inspires a women-led CAA protest in Kolkata's Park Circus |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/politics/kolkata-caa-protest-park-circus-women |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Caravan |date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ghatak |first1=Anchita |title=At Kolkata's Park Circus, Another Women's Sit-In Protest Keeps the Struggle Going |url=https://thewire.in/rights/kolkata-park-circus-anti-caa-protest-women |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The WIre |date=15 January 2020}}</ref> On request from the protesters, the [[Government of West Bengal|West Bengal state government]] provided them with tents, bio-toilets, running water and lights so their protest could run continuously.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kolkata: Park Circus protesters get bio-toilets, running water |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/park-circus-protesters-get-bio-toilets-running-water/articleshow/73340756.cms |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=18 January 2020}}</ref> Former Union Minister [[P.&nbsp;Chidambaram]] visited the protest and conducted a workshop there on CAA and NRC. Social activist [[Yogendra Yadav]] and singer [[Kabir Suman]] also visited to extend their support to the protesters.<ref>{{cite news |title=Park Circus protest site Chidambaram's first port of call in Kolkata |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/park-circus-protest-site-chidambaram-s-first-port-of-call-in-kolkata/story-FVoUqpuEKrVdsjT3k7ISYP.html |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Hindustan Times |date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Protests inspired by Shaheen Bagh\n!Location\n!Area\n!Start\n!Active\n!Duration{{Update inline|date=February 2020}}\n!Ref\n|-\n|Kolkata, West Bengal\n|[[Park Circus]]\n|7 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=7|year1=2020|month2=2|day2=28|year2=2020}} on 28 Feb\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kolkatas-shaheen-bagh-like-protest-park-circus-maidan-protest-enters-23rd-day-2171434|title=Kolkata's Shaheen Bagh-Like Protest Enters 23rd Day, Gets Support From Artistes, Politicians|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/park-circus-protest-completes-a-month/articleshow/73969734.cms|title=Park Circus protest completes a month {{!}} Kolkata News - Times of India|last=Mitra|first=Dipawali|date=6 February 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://frontline.thehindu.com/the-nation/article30800912.ece|title=Kolkata's Shaheen Bagh|last=Chattopadhyay|first=Suhrid Sankar|date=28 February 2020|website=Frontline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|Bengaluru, Karnataka\n|Bilal Bagh\n|8 February 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=2|day1=8|year1=2020|month2=3|day2=15|year2=2020}} on 15 Mar\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/city/bengaluru-coronavirus-can-t-stop-us-say-bilal-bagh-protesters-814124.html|title=Bengaluru: Coronavirus can't stop us, say Bilal Bagh protesters|date=2020-03-16|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|Parbhani, Maharashtra\n|Shaheen Bagh, Dharna ground\n|20 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=2|day2=18|year2=2020}} on 18 Feb\n|<ref name=\"inquilab.com\">{{cite news | title= Shaheen Bagh style protest also begins in Parbhani |url=https://www.inquilab.com/news/articles/shaheen-bagh-style-protest-also-begins-in-parbhani-11351| access-date =25 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Mumbai, Maharashtra\n|Nagpada\n|26 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=26|year1=2020|month2=3|day2=4|year2=2020}} on 4 Mar\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/mumbai-news/at-least-100-women-continue-sit-in-protest-against-citizenship-amendment-act-in-mumbai-on-2nd-day-2171014|title=Mumbai Women, Inspired By Shaheen Bagh Sit-In, Protest Against CAA|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/mumbai-news/case-registered-against-anti-caa-protesters-in-mumbai-2177254|title=Case Registered Against Anti-CAA Protesters In Mumbai|last=PTI|date=8 February 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/mumbai-bagh-protest-police|title=Police's Stern Response Fails to Dampen the Spirit of Women in Mumbai Bagh|last=Shantha|first=Sukanya|date=11 February 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref><ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/mumbai-police-commissioner-param-bir-singh-takes-over|title='Won't Allow Delhi-Like Violence': New Mumbai Police Commissioner|last=Sinha|first=Ankita|date=2020-03-04|website=The Quint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n|-\n|YMCA ground, Agripada\n|17 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=17|year1=2020|month2=3|day2=4|year2=2020}} on 4 Mar\n|<ref name=\"MumProtestYMCA\" /><ref name=\":19\" />\n|-\n|Malerkotla, Punjab\n|Anaj Mandi\n|9 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=9|year1=2020|month2=2|day2=20|year2=2020}} on 20 Feb\t\n|<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ghazali |first1=Mohammed |last2=Dey |first2=Stela |title=Punjab's Biggest Anti-Citizenship Law Protest Held In Malerkotla |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/punjabs-biggest-anti-citizenship-law-protest-held-in-malerkotla-2182815 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The NDTV |date=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Ranchi, Jharkhand\n|Haj House\n|19/20 January 2020\n|No\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=19|year1=2020|month2=3|day2=21|year2=2020}} on 21 March\t\n|<ref>{{cite news |title=Unhindered, Ranchi's 'Shaheen Bagh' completes 1 month |url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/unhindered--ranchi---s----shaheen-bagh----completes-1-month.html |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Pioneer |date=19 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kumar |first1=Raj |title=Panic at Jharkhand's Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/jharkhand/panic-at-jharkhands-shaheen-bagh/cid/1742003 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Telegraph (Calcutta) |date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/two-months-on-ranchi-s-saheen-bagh-stir-suspended-till-april-5/story-iySb1fqguqmnKCgE4dUtgJ.html</ref>\n| Suspended till 5th April due to [[coronavirus pandemic]]\n|-\n|Deoband, Uttar Pradesh\n|Idgah ground\n|27 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=27|year1=2020|month2=2|day2=6|year2=2020}} on 6 Feb\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/anti-caa-protest-up-deoband|title='There Is No Going Back': Women Lead Shaheen Bagh-Style Protest in UP's Deoband|last=Shantha|first=Sukanya|date=6 February 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n|-\n|Prayagraj, Uttar Pradesh\n|Mansoor Ali Park \n|12 January 2020\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=1|day1=12|year1=2020|month2=1|day2=25|year2=2020}} on 25 Jan\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/cold-no-bar-for-protesters-at-roshan-bagh/articleshow/73593589.cms|title=Cold no bar for protesters at Roshan Bagh|last=|first=|date=25 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://janataweekly.org/shaheen-bagh-inspired-protests-spread-across-the-country/|title=Shaheen Bagh-Inspired Protests Spread Across the Country \u2013 Janata Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|Gaya, Bihar\n|Shanti Bagh\n|29 December 2019\n|Yes\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=12|day1=29|year1=2019|month2=1|day2=29|year2=2020}} on 29 Jan\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.siasat.com/caa-nrc-gayas-shanti-bagh-turns-mini-shaheen-bagh-1791735/|title=CAA-NRC: Gaya's Shanti Bagh turns into mini Shaheen Bagh|date=2020-01-13|website=The Siasat Daily|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|Chennai, Tamil Nadu\n|Old Washermanpet\n|14 February 2020\n|No{{Efn|Called off till 31 March due to coronavirus pandemic|name=|group=}}\n|{{Age in years and days|month1=2|day1=14|year1=2020|month2=March|day2=18|year2=2020}} on 18 March\n|<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jayarajan |first1=Sreedevi |title='Will fight any govt that divides us': Women continue Chennai's Shaheen Bagh protest |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/will-fight-any-govt-divides-us-women-continue-chennais-shaheen-bagh-protest-118478 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The News Minute |date=19 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Naig |first1=Udhav |title=Shaheen Bagh-style anti-CAA protest enters day 3 in Chennai |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/shaheen-bagh-style-stirenters-day-3-in-chennai/article30837618.ece |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/18/shaheen-bagh-of-chennai-calls-off-protest-temporarily-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.html|title=Shaheen Bagh of Chennai 'temporarily' calls off protests amid coronavirus outbreak|last=Subramanian|first=Lakshmi|date=18 March 2020|website=The Week|language=en|others=Web Desk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|Jaffrabad, Delhi\n|[[Jaffrabad, Delhi|Jaffrabad]]\n|\n|Yes\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/women-from-across-country-pledge-support-to-shaheen-bagh-protesters-2192017|title=Women From Across Country Pledge Support To Shaheen Bagh Protesters|last=|first=|date=9 March 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|}\nOn 11 January, an all-women sit-in protest started outside Konark Mall in Kondhwa, [[Pune]], organized by Kul Jamaat-e-Tanzeem, an umbrella body of several organisations. This protest started with a few participants and steadily grew a crowd which reached around 500\u2013600 protesters on 19&nbsp;January. According to a protester the movement was to save the constitution and the country. Candle light vigils, human chains and speeches were part of the protest. The venue had banners with slogans such as \"Tumhari Lathi Se Tej Hamari Awaaz Hai\" and \"Liar Liar Desh on Fire\", as well as \"India Needs Education, Jobs, Not CAA, NRC, NPR\".<ref name=\"19 Jan Pune Shaheen\">{{cite news |title=Pune 'Shaheen Bagh in Kondhwa' anti-CAA protest enters ninth day |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/jan/19/pune-shaheen-bagh-in-kondhwa-anti-caa-protest-enters-ninth-day-2091592.html |work=The New Indian Express |date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January, a group of women started a CAA sit-in demonstration in the market area of Patna's Sabzibagh. Over the following three days, people of all ages gathered to join them in the protest.<ref>{{cite news |title=Slogans of Shaheen Bagh Echo at Patna's Sabzibagh |url=https://thewire.in/women/shaheen-bagh-patna-sabzibagh-caa-protests |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Wire |date=15 January 2020}}</ref> Also on 12 January, inspired by the women of Shaheen Bagh, groups of ten women began sit-in protests at the Mansoor Ali Park of Roshan Bagh, Allahabad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jafri |first1=Abdul |title=CAA-NRC: Shaheen Bagh-Inspired Protests Spread to Allahabad Via Kanpur |url=https://www.newsclick.in/CAA-NRC-Shaheen-Bagh-Inspired-Protests-Spread-Allahabad-Kanpur |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The news Click |date=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Anti-CAA stir: Women continue protest on sixth day, offer Friday prayers |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cities/anti-caa-stir-women-continue-protest-on-sixth-day-offer-friday-prayers/story-jCaU1PUenopo0JsWplKWWO.html |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Hindustan Times |date=17 January 2020}}</ref> Over the next few days, thousands of women, students, and others braved rain and cold to join the resistance against the CAA-NRC through slogans, speeches and poems.<ref>{{cite news |title=Anti CAA protestPrayagraj's mansoor Ali becomes delhi's Shaheen bagh Park |url=http://www.uniindia.com/anti-caa-protests-prayagraj-s-mansoor-ali-park-becomes-delhi-s-shaheen-bagh/north/news/1856557.html |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=United News of India |date=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Protest continues at Roshan Bagh area of Allahabad against CAA, NRC |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/allahabad/protest-continues-at-roshan-bagh-area-of-allahabad-against-caa-nrc/articleshow/73359660.cms |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=18 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nSimilar protests were held at Kanpur's [[Chaman Ganj, Kanpur|Chaman Ganj]], Gaya's Shanti Bagh,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ameen |first1=Faruqh |title=Shaheen Bagh inspires many protests across the country |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/shaheen-bagh-inspires-many-protests-across-the-country/cid/1736089 |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Telegraph Calcutta |date=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Sameer |title=CAA-NRC: Gaya's Shanti Bagh turns into mini Shaheen Bagh |url=https://www.siasat.com/caa-nrc-gayas-shanti-bagh-turns-mini-shaheen-bagh-1791735/ |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Siasat Daily |date=13 January 2020}}</ref> [[Kota, Rajasthan|Kota]]'s Eidgah ground,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/jaipur/how-can-kota-women-be-behind-say-protesters-after-launching-shaheen-bagh-like-protest-in-city/story-vgy6BhajL1KkwKGVhkf8eL.html|title='How can Kota women be behind?' say protesters after launching Shaheen Bagh-like protest in city|date=2020-01-15|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref> Lucknow's [[Husainabad Clock Tower|Clock Tower]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Awasthi |first1=Puja |title=Lucknow's 'Shaheen Bagh': Women start sit-in against CAA at iconic clock tower |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/01/18/lucknow-shaheen-bagh-women-start-sit-in-against-caa-at-iconic-clock-tower.html |accessdate=21 January 2020 |work=The Week |date=18 January 2020}}</ref> and [[Fraser Town, Bangalore|Fraser Town]] in Bangalore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/bangalore/bengaluru-taking-queue-from-shaheen-bagh-women-hold-24-hour-protest-at-frazer-town-6232999/|title=Bengaluru: Taking cue from Shaheen Bagh, women hold 24-hour protest at Frazer Town|last=Arakal|first=Ralph Alex|date=2020-01-24|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>  Inspired by the Shaheen Bagh protest, a massive anti-CAA-NRC-NPR protest started in Mumbai on 17 January. Around 10,000 women gathered in the evening at the YMCA ground in Mumbai to protest. The protest was organised by NGO collective Mumbai Citizen Quorum.<ref name=\"MumProtestYMCA\">{{cite news |last1=Iyer |first1=Rudrika |title=Mumbai: 10,000 women lend their voice to anti-CAA protest |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/mumbai-10000-women-lend-their-voice-to-anti-caa-protest/articleshow/73350759.cms |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Times of India |date=18 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Inspired by Shaheen Bagh, women hold a massive anti-CAA protest at Mumbai's YMCA ground |url=https://indianexpress.com/photos/india-news/inspired-by-shaheen-bagh-women-hold-a-massive-anti-caa-protest-at-mumbais-ymca-ground-6222721/2/ |accessdate=19 January 2020 |work=The Indian Express |date=18 January 2020}}</ref> On 20 January, an indefinite sit-in protest started at Parbhani, called \"Parbhani bhi ek Shaheen Bagh\", which was organised by Samvidhan Bachao Tahrik.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lokmat.com/parabhani/parbhani-protests-against-caa-next-day/amp/|title=CAA protests continued at Parbhani on 2nd day|last=|first=|date=22 January 2020|work=[[Lokmat]]|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"inquilab.com\"/>\n\n== Delhi Assembly election issue ==\nThe blockade at Shaheen Bagh became a campaign issue for the [[2020 Delhi Legislative Assembly election|Delhi Legislative Assembly election]], held on 8&nbsp;February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/delhi-polls-bjp-doesnt-want-to-open-shaheen-bagh-route-its-doing-dirty-politics-over-this-issue-says-arvind-kejriwal/articleshow/73660231.cms|title=Delhi elections 2020: BJP doesn't want to open Shaheen Bagh route, it's doing dirty politics over this issue, says Arvind Kejriwal|last=|first=|date=27 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Chief Minister of Delhi [[Arvind Kejriwal]] [[Aam Aadmi Party]] and Home Minister of India [[Amit Shah]] fiercely criticized each other over their positions on the protest. On 27&nbsp;January, during an election rally, Shah said that the protesters would not listen to the BJP government regarding the removal of the road block. Shah asked Kejriwal whether \"he is with the people of Shaheen Bagh or not\" as some AAP members had publicly sided with the protesters. Kejriwal accused the BJP of using \"dirty politics\" and prolonging the road closures to cause a public backlash against the protesters, and noted their promises to reopen the route following the election meant that they could do so at any time. He urged the BJP leadership to visit Shaheen Bagh, talk with the protesters, and open the blockade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/gloves-off-cm-arvind-kejriwal-and-amit-shah-attack-each-other-over-shaheen-bagh/articleshow/73678913.cms|title=Gloves off, CM Arvind Kejriwal and Amit Shah attack each other over Shaheen Bagh|last=Mishra|first=Alok KN|date=28 January 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Amit Shah dares Kejriwal to visit Shaheen Bagh, asserts Modi govt will not spare anti-nationals|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/national-politics/amit-shah-dares-kejriwal-to-visit-shaheen-bagh-asserts-modi-govt-will-not-spare-anti-nationals-798830.html |accessdate=28 January 2020 |work=The Deccan Herald |date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnion Law Minister [[Ravi Shankar Prasad]] (BJP) said that Shaheen Bagh is offering a platform for the \"anti-India\" gangs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/delhi-assembly-polls-2020/story/can-shaheen-bagh-swing-delhi-assembly-election-1640845-2020-01-28|title=Can Shaheen Bagh swing Delhi Assembly election?|last=Dutta|first=Prabhash K.|date=28 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Junior finance minister [[Parvesh Verma]] (BJP) made hateful and abusive comments about the Shaheen Bagh protesters and claimed that they would be cleared within an hour of the election results being declared on 11 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/delhi-election-2020-parvesh-sahib-singh-verma-says-no-shaheen-bagh-protesters-mosques-on-state-land-2170674|title=\"They Will Rape, Kill\": Delhi BJP MP's Shocker On Shaheen Bagh Protesters|last=Dwivedi|first=Sukirti|date=28 January 2020|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> Verma was later penalised by the [[Election Commission of India|Election Commission]] and BJP for his comments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51276867|title=MPs penalised for comments on peaceful protesters|date=2020-01-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other BJP leaders made statements regarding removal of the protesters from Shaheen Bagh. One said that a \"surgical strike\" would be conducted on the protesters on 11 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/delhi-assembly-polls-2020/story/tajinder-bagga-bjp-on-shaheen-bagh-1641578-2020-01-30|title=BJP's Tajinder Bagga warns Shaheen Bagh of surgical strike on Feb 11|last=Udayakumar|first=Ganesh Radha|date=30 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> [[Hindu Sena]] stated that they would remove all \"Shaheen Bagh Jihadis\" at 11&nbsp;am on 2 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shaheen-bagh-anti-caa-protest-hindu-sena-chief-1641418-2020-01-29|title=Shaheen Bagh 'Jihadis' inciting division of India, will remove them on Feb 2: Hindu Sena|last=Pandey|first=Tanushree|date=29 January 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> This plan was cancelled after consultations with the Delhi Police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/rights/hindu-sena-shaheen-bagh-protersters|title=Hindu Sena Calls Off Plan to Unleash Violence on Shaheen Bagh Protesters|last=|first=|date=2 February 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Threats to the protesters ===\nSeveral BJP leaders and politicians made hate speeches against the protesters, including [[Yogi Adityanath]], [[Anurag Thakur]] and [[Parvesh Verma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/man-fires-bullets-in-shaheen-bagh-area/articleshow/73843412.cms|title=Man fires two rounds in air in Shaheen Bagh area; taken into custody.|date=1 February 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.in/entry/anurag-thakur-goli-maro-chants-at-delhi-election-rally_in_5e2f9a7bc5b68f86c8cd03b5|title=Anurag Thakur On 'Goli Maro' Chants At Poll Rally: 'People Reacted. What Can I Do?|last1=Sebastian|first1=Meryl|date=28 January 2020|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> This was followed by attempts to threaten the protesters. On 28 January 2020, an armed man entered the Shaheen Bagh protest site, climbed the stage, and threatened people to stop the agitation; he was later overpowered by protesters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/armed-man-threatens-shaheen-bagh-protesters-overpowered/article30676177.ece|title=Armed man threatens Shaheen Bagh protesters, overpowered|date=28 January 2020|work=The Hindu|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> On 1 February, a [[Hindutva|Hindu fundamentalist]] entered the barricaded area and fired a gun into the air near the stage; he was taken into police custody.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://scroll.in/video/951843/i-am-kapil-gujjar-listen-to-the-man-who-fired-a-gun-at-shaheen-bagh-explain-his-reason|title='I am Kapil Gujjar': Listen to the man who fired a gun at Shaheen Bagh explain his reason|date=1 February 2020|work=The Scroll|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/india-news-man-opens-fire-near-shaheen-bagh-protest-site/346608|title='...Sirf Hinduon Ki Chalegi': Man Opens Fire Near Shaheen Bagh Protest Site|date=1 February 2020|work=The Outlook India|accessdate=1 February 2020|publisher=The India Today}}</ref> The incident happened two days after a Hindu fundamentalist shot and injured a student protester in the presence of police near [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/shots-fired-at-delhis-shaheen-bagh-days-after-jamia-shooting-man-taken-into-custody-2482733.html|title=Man Opens Fire in Delhi's Shaheen Bagh 2 Days After Jamia Shooting, Shouts 'Only Hindus Will Rule'|date=1 February 2020|work=The News18|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/in-2nd-incident-man-opens-fire-in-shaheen-bagh-detained/1723624|title=In 2nd incident, man opens fire in Shaheen Bagh; detained|date=1 February 2020|work=The Outlook India|accessdate=1 February 2020|publisher=The India Today}}</ref> The alleged perpetrator of the Jamia incident had made various threatening and hateful social media posts, including one in which he threatened to convert \"Shaheen Bagh into Jallianwala Bagh\", the [[Jallianwala Bagh massacre|site of a massacre]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://in.news.yahoo.com/gunman-behind-jamia-shooting-123730614.html|title=Who is the gunman behind Jamia shooting?|date=30 January 2020|work=Yahoo|accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref> On 2 February 2020, the [[Election Commission of India]] transferred Chinmoy Biswal, the then deputy commissioner of police (DCP) for [[South East Delhi district|South East Delhi]], citing the multiple shooting incidents in the Jamia area, which was an election polling area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/ec-transfers-dcp-south-east-chinmoy-biswal-after-jamia-shaheen-bagh-firing-incidents-1642642-2020-02-02|title=EC transfers Delhi Police DCP Chinmoy Biswal after Jamia, Shaheen Bagh firing incidents|date=2 February 2020|work=The India Today|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact of coronavirus pandemic ==\nFollowing the spread of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus in India]] in 2020, the ''[[Press Trust of India]]'' reported that the women at Shaheen Bagh had said that \"the protesters were being provided with masks and hand sanitisers and there was no need to be scared.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-curb-on-gatherings-over-coronavirus-applies-to-shaheen-bagh-delhi-chief-ministe-2195819|title=Curb On Gatherings Over Coronavirus Applies To Shaheen Bagh, Arvind Kejriwal Clarifies|last=|first=|date=17 March 2020|editor-last=Sanyal|editor-first=Anindita|work=The NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> However, the [[Chief Minister of Delhi]] made it clear that restrictions were in place in Delhi as per the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] and this applied to protests too. Schools, colleges, malls, weekly markets, cinema halls and gatherings of more than 50 people have been banned in Delhi.<ref name=\":20\" /> The Chief Minister made it clear that those who did not comply with the Act would be punished.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51907173|title=Why coronavirus may halt months-long India protest|date=2020-03-16|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> However, the coordinators stated that \"the order of shut down has come for entertainment services, while Shaheen Bagh is agitation and fight for survival\" and that only a Supreme Court order could get them to move.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/shaheen-bagh-protesters-to-be-removed-as-coronavirus-precautionary-measure/article31089679.ece|title=Shaheen Bagh protesters to be removed as precautionary measure|last=Awasthi|first=Prashasti|date=17 March 2020|publisher=The Hindu|work=The Businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> As a precautionary measure the protesters planned for a \"controlled gathering\".<ref name=\"HT SBagh 1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/shaheen-bagh-protest-on-despite-health-risk/story-myJmOAhQItEqxh73i0XSiI.html|title=Shaheen Bagh protest on despite health risk|date=2020-03-14|work=The Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nThe protest followed the \"[[Janata Curfew]]\", a self-imposed [[curfew]] annoucned by the Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on 22 March 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/4-hour-cap-kids-and-elderly-barred-no-mics-coronavirus-tweaks-to-shaheen-bagh-protests-2545191.html|title=4-Hour Cap, Kids and Elderly Barred, No Mics: Coronavirus Tweaks to Shaheen Bagh Protests|last=|first=|date=21 March 2020|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> by reducing the number of protesters to 5 and symbolically leaving behind cots and sandals by other protesters at the site in solidarity.<ref name=\"SB corona outbreak\">{{cite news |title=As Shaheen Bagh Sticks to 5 Protester Limit, Vigilante Attacks Site With Petrol Bomb |url=https://thewire.in/communalism/petrol-bomb-shaheen-bagh-janata-curfew |work=The Wire|accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> However, a complete [[lockdown]] was imposed in Delhi by Chief Minister [[Arvind Kejriwal]] from 23 to 31 March 2020, folowing which the protesters were removed by the Delhi police on 24 March 2020.<ref name=\"100days\"/> It was reported that the police arrested the protesters who were present there as they refused to end the protest and leave the site.<ref name=\"100days\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Shaheen Bagh protest site cleared by police as Delhi goes under coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/delhi-lockdown-coronavirus-shaheen-bagh-protest-cleared-1658927-2020-03-24 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The India Today |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"120\">\nFile:No Cash No Paytm No Account Shaheen Bagh Protests 1 Jan 2020.jpg\nFile:Volunteers getting books and posters for protestors shaheen bagh new delhi 7 jan 2020.jpg\nFile:No CCA graffiti on a police barridcade in New Delhi 8 Jan 2020.jpg\nFile:Shaheen Bagh on the eve of New Year.jpg\nFile:Standing in solidarity with AMU JNU Jamia Shaheen Bagh anti CAA NRC police brutality protests New Delhi 8 Jan 2020.jpg\nFile:Slogan against ABVP at Shaheen Bagh protests 11 Jan 2020.jpg\nFile:The colour I belong to is tricolour not saffron At Shaheen Bagh protests 11 Jan 2020.jpg\nFile:A photo wall curated by the youth of Jamia Miliia Islamia University 28 Jan 2020 at Shaheen Bagh protests.jpg\nFile:Footbridge shaheen bagh covered in anti nrc caa posters new delhi 7 jan 2020.jpg\nFile:Handmade posters at Shaheen Bagh protests.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|India|Politics|Law|History|Freedom of speech|Society}}\n* [[Protests of 2019]]\n*[[Irom Chanu Sharmila]]\n* [[2020 Women's March]]\n* [[2019\u201320 French pension reform strike]]\n* [[Yellow vests movement]]\n*[[No NRC 